pire 1959\u20131965\n|last=Wood\n|first=J R T\n|date=June 2005\n|location=Victoria, British Columbia\n|publisher=[[Trafford Publishing]]\n|isbn=978-1-4120-4952-8\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=A Matter of Weeks Rather Than Months: The Impasse Between Harold Wilson and Ian Smith: Sanctions, Aborted Settlements and War 1965\u20131969\n|last=Wood\n|first=J R T\n|date=April 2008\n|location=Victoria, British Columbia\n|publisher=Trafford Publishing\n|isbn=978-1-4251-4807-2\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=Rhodesia and Independence: A Study in British Colonial Policy\n|last=Young\n|first=Kenneth\n|year=1969\n|origyear=1967\n|location=London\n|publisher=[[J. M. Dent|J M Dent & Sons]]\n|oclc=955160\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=SouthScan. ''Volume 7''\n|year=1992\n|location=London\n|publisher=SouthScan\n|oclc=955160\n|ref={{harvid|Southscan|1992}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = Deputy Prime Minister of Southern Rhodesia\n  | years = 1962{{spaced ndash}}1964\n  | before =\n  | after = [[Clifford Dupont]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = [[Finance Minister|Minister of the Treasury of Southern Rhodesia]]\n  | years = 1962{{spaced ndash}}1964\n  | before =\n  | after  = [[John Wrathall]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  |title=[[Prime Minister of Rhodesia]]|\n  |years=1964{{spaced ndash}}1979|\n  |before=[[Winston Field]]|\n  |after=[[Abel Muzorewa]]<br />(of [[Zimbabwe-Rhodesia]])\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Ian Smith}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Signatories of the Unilateral Declaration of Independence}}\n{{ZimbabwePMs}}\n{{Zimbabwe-Ministers of Finance}}\n{{Zimbabwe-Ministers of Foreign Affairs}}}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Ian}}\n[[Category:Ian Smith| ]]\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Zimbabwean politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Chaplin High School]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cerebrovascular disease]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Assembly (Zimbabwe)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:People from Midlands Province]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Rhodesia]]\n[[Category:Rhodes University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian Front politicians]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian Air Force personnel]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian farmers]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian memoirists]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian politicians]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Shot-down aviators]]\n[[Category:Signatories of Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence]]\n[[Category:Southern Rhodesian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Southern Rhodesian World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:White Rhodesian people]]\n[[Category:White Zimbabwean politicians]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriates in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean farmers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean Presbyterians]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Rhodesian prime minister|other uses|Ian Smith (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|20th-century Prime Minister of Rhodesia}}\n{{POV|date=March 2020}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =[[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = Ian Douglas Smith\n| honorific-suffix = [[Legion of Merit (Rhodesia)|GCLM]] [[Independence Decoration (Rhodesia)|ID]]\n| image            = Ian Smith 1950s.jpg\n| image_upright    = 0.8\n| caption          = Smith {{circa}}&nbsp;1954\n| alt              = A black and white photograph of Ian Smith\n| order            = 8th\n| office           = Prime Minister of Rhodesia\n| term_start       = 13 April 1964\n| term_end         = 1 June 1979{{refn|In the eyes of the UK, Smith legally stopped being Prime Minister when his government [[Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence|declared independence]] on 11 November 1965.{{sfn|Wood|1999}} In practice, he remained in office until 1979.{{sfn|Oxford DNB}}|group=n|name=\"defacto\"}}\n| monarch          = {{plainlist|\n* [[Elizabeth II]]\n* (to 1965 or 1970){{refn|Elizabeth II's representative in Rhodesia\u2014the [[Governor of Southern Rhodesia|Governor]], [[Sir Humphrey Gibbs]]\u2014dismissed Smith upon the declaration of independence, but Smith continued to maintain staunch allegiance to the Queen until 1970.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=471}}|group=n|name=\"endedqueen\"}}}}\n| president        = {{plainlist|\n* [[Clifford Dupont]] (1970\u201375)\n* [[John Wrathall]] (1976\u201378){{refn|Acting presidents were [[Henry Everard]] (1975\u201376, August\u2013November 1978 and March\u2013June 1979) and [[Jack William Pithey]] (1978\u201379).{{sfn|Oxford DNB}}|group=n|name=\"actingpres\"}}}}\n| predecessor      = [[Winston Field]]\n| successor        = [[Abel Muzorewa]] (as PM of Zimbabwe Rhodesia)\n| order2 = [[Leader of the Opposition]] of Zimbabwe\n| term_start2 = 18 April 1980\n| term_end2 = May 1987\n| president2 = [[Canaan Banana]]{{sfn|Oxford DNB}}\n| primeminister2 = [[Robert Mugabe]]\n| birth_name       = Ian Douglas Smith\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1919|4|8}}\n| birth_place      = [[Shurugwi|Selukwe]], [[Company rule in Rhodesia|Southern Rhodesia]]{{refn|Selukwe and Shurugwi are the same place; the town was [[place names in Zimbabwe|renamed]] in 1982.{{sfn|Caute|1983|p=440}}|group=n|name=\"selukwe\"}}\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|2007|11|20|1919|4|8}}\n| death_place      = [[Cape Town]], South Africa\n| resting_place    = {{plainlist|\n* Near [[Shurugwi]], Zimbabwe\n* (ashes scattered){{refn||group=n|name=\"selukwe\"}}}}\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Janet Smith (Rhodesia)|Janet Duvenage Smith (''n\u00e9e'' Watt)]]|August 1948|3 December 1994|end=died}}\n| relations        =\n| children         = {{plainlist|\n* Jean <small>(stepdaughter)</small>\n* Robert <small>(stepson)</small>\n* [[Alec Smith|Alec]]}}\n| party            = {{plainlist|\n* [[Southern Rhodesia Liberal Party|Liberal]] <small>(1948\u201353)</small>\n* [[United Federal Party|United Federal]] <small>(1953\u201361)</small>\n* [[Rhodesian Front]] <small>and successors (1962\u201387)</small>}}\n| alma_mater       = [[Rhodes University]]\n| footnotes        =\n<!-- Military service -->\n| allegiance = {{plainlist|\n* Southern Rhodesia\n* United Kingdom\n}}\n| branch = [[Royal Air Force]]\n| serviceyears = [[Military service of Ian Smith|1941\u20131945]]\n| rank = [[Flight Lieutenant]]\n| battles = [[Second World War]]\n}}\n\n'''Ian Douglas Smith''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Legion of Merit (Rhodesia)|GCLM]] [[Independence Decoration (Rhodesia)|ID]]}} (8 April 1919&nbsp;\u2013 20 November 2007) was a politician, farmer, and fighter pilot who served as [[Prime Minister of Rhodesia|Prime Minister]] of [[Rhodesia]] (or [[Southern Rhodesia]]; today [[Zimbabwe]]) from 1964 to 1979.{{refn||group=n|name=\"defacto\"}} He was the country's first premier not born abroad, and led the predominantly white government that [[Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence|unilaterally declared independence]] from the [[United Kingdom]] in 1965, following prolonged dispute over the terms. He remained Prime Minister for almost all of the 14 years of international isolation that followed, and oversaw Rhodesia's [[Rhodesian Security Forces|security forces]] during most of the [[Rhodesian Bush War|Bush War]], which pitted the [[list of historical unrecognized states|unrecognised]] administration against communist-backed black nationalist guerrilla groups. Smith, who has been described as personifying white Rhodesia, remains a highly controversial figure\u2014supporters venerate him as a man of integrity and vision who understood the uncomfortable truths of Africa,{{sfn|BBC|2007}}{{vague|date=December 2019}} while critics describe an unrepentant racist whose policies and actions caused the deaths of thousands and contributed to Zimbabwe's later crises.\n\nSmith was born to British immigrants in [[Selukwe]], a small town in the Southern Rhodesian [[Midlands Province|Midlands]], four years before the colony became [[responsible government|self-governing]] in 1923. During the [[Second World War]], he [[Military service of Ian Smith|served as]] a [[Royal Air Force]] fighter pilot. A crash in Egypt caused debilitating facial and bodily wounds that remained conspicuous for the rest of his life; following rehabilitation, he served in Europe, where he was shot down and fought alongside Italian partisans. He set up a farm in his home town in 1948, and the same year, [[1948 Southern Rhodesia general election|became Member of Parliament]] for Selukwe{{mdash}}at 29 years old, the country's youngest ever MP. Originally a [[Southern Rhodesia Liberal Party|Liberal]], he defected to the [[United Federal Party]] in 1953, and served as [[Chief Whip]] from 1958 onwards. He left that party in 1961 in protest at the territory's new constitution, and in the following year helped [[Winston Field]] to form the all-white, firmly conservative [[Rhodesian Front]], which called for independence without an immediate shift to majority rule.\n\nSmith became Deputy Prime Minister following the Rhodesian Front's December 1962 [[1962 Southern Rhodesian general election|election victory]], and stepped up to the premiership after Field resigned in April 1964. With the UK government refusing to grant independence while Rhodesia did not devise a set timetable for the introduction of majority rule, talks with the UK Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]] repeatedly broke down, leading Smith and his [[Cabinet of Rhodesia|Cabinet]] to declare independence on 11 November 1965. His government endured in the face of [[United Nations]] economic sanctions with the assistance of South Africa and, [[Carnation Revolution|until 1974]], Portugal. Talks with the UK in 1966, 1968 and 1971 came to nothing. Smith declared Rhodesia a republic in 1970 and led the RF to three more decisive election victories over the next seven years. After the Bush War began in earnest in 1972, he negotiated with the non-militant nationalist leader Bishop [[Abel Muzorewa]] and the rival guerrilla movements headed by [[Joshua Nkomo]] and [[Robert Mugabe]].\n\nIn 1978, Smith and non-militant nationalists including Muzorewa signed the [[Internal Settlement]], under which the country became [[Zimbabwe Rhodesia]] in 1979. Mugabe and Nkomo continued fighting; no country recognised the settlement. Smith was part of Muzorewa's delegation that settled with the UK and the revolutionary guerrillas at [[Lancaster House Agreement|Lancaster House]], and, following Zimbabwe's recognised independence in 1980, he was [[Leader of the Opposition]] during Mugabe's first seven years in power. Smith was a stridently vocal critic of the Mugabe government both before and after his retirement from frontline politics in 1987; he dedicated much of his 1997 memoirs, ''[[The Great Betrayal: The Memoirs of Ian Douglas Smith|The Great Betrayal]]'', to condemning Mugabe and several UK politicians. As Mugabe's reputation thereafter plummeted amid Zimbabwe's economic ruin, reckoning of Smith and his legacy improved.{{sfn|Boynton|2007}} Zimbabwean opposition supporters lauded the elderly Smith as an immovable symbol of resistance. He remained in Zimbabwe until 2005, when he moved to [[Cape Town]], South Africa, for medical reasons. After his death two years later at the age of 88, his ashes were repatriated and scattered at his farm.\n\n==Early life and education==\n===Family, childhood and adolescence===\n[[File:Jock and Agnes Smith, 1935.jpg|thumb|Smith's parents, Jock and Agnes, in 1935. Jock emigrated to Rhodesia from Scotland in 1898; Agnes arrived from England in 1906.|alt=A photograph of a middle-aged man and woman]]\n\nIan Douglas Smith was born on 8 April 1919 in [[Selukwe]], a small mining and farming town about {{convert|310|km|abbr=on}} southwest of the [[Southern Rhodesia]]n capital [[Harare|Salisbury]]. He had two elder sisters, Phyllis and Joan.{{refn|A younger brother named Hilary, born in 1923, died of [[pneumonia]] in infancy.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=41}}|group=n|name=\"hilary\"}} His father, John Douglas \"Jock\" Smith, originally came from [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]], Scotland; the son of a cattle breeder and [[butcher]], he had emigrated to Rhodesia as an eighteen-year-old in 1898, and become a prominent rancher, butcher, miner and garage owner in Selukwe. Jock and his English wife, Agnes (''n\u00e9e'' Hodgson), had met in 1907, when she was sixteen, a year after her family's emigration to Selukwe from [[Frizington]], [[Cumberland]]. After Mr Hodgson sent his wife and children back to England in 1908, Jock Smith astonished them in 1911 by arriving unannounced in Cumberland to ask for Agnes' hand; they had not seen each other for three years. They married in Frizington and returned together to Rhodesia, where Jock, an accomplished horseman, won the 1911 Coronation Derby at Salisbury.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=36\u201338}}\n\nThe Smiths involved themselves heavily in local affairs. Jock chaired the village management board and commanded the Selukwe Company of the [[Southern Rhodesia Volunteers]]; he also became a founding member of the Selukwe [[Freemasons]]' Lodge and president of the town's football and rugby clubs. Agnes, who became informally known as \"Mrs Jock\", established and ran the Selukwe [[Women's Institute]]. Both were appointed [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (at different times) for their services to the community.<ref>{{harvnb|Berlyn|1978|pp=39\u201340}}. See also ''[[The London Gazette]]'': [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/40053/supplement/23 (Supplement) No.&nbsp;40053. p.&nbsp;23]. 1 January 1954. and [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/41909/supplement/23 (Supplement) No.&nbsp;41909. p.&nbsp;23]. 1 January 1960. Both accessed 14 October 2014.</ref> \"My parents strove to instil principles and moral virtues, the sense of right and wrong, of integrity, in their children,\" Smith wrote in his memoirs. \"They set wonderful examples to live up to.\"{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=7}} He considered his father \"a man of extremely strong principles\"{{sfn|Van Rensburg|1975|p=314}}\u2014\"one of the fairest men I have ever met and that is the way he brought me up. He always told me that we're entitled to our half of the country and the blacks are entitled to theirs.\"{{sfn|Time|1976}} Raised on the frontier of the [[British Empire]] in the UK's youngest [[settler colonialism|settler colony]], Smith and his generation of [[white people in Zimbabwe|white Rhodesians]] grew up with a reputation for being \"more British than the British\", something in which they took great pride.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=1}}\n\nSmith showed sporting promise from an early age. After attending the Selukwe primary school, he boarded at [[Chaplin High School|Chaplin School]] in [[Gweru|Gwelo]], about {{convert|30|km|abbr=on}} away. In his final year at Chaplin, he was head [[prefect]] captain of the school teams in cricket, rugby and tennis, recipient of the [[Victor Ludorum]] in athletics, and the school's outstanding rifle marksman.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=42\u201343}} \"I was an absolute lunatic about sport,\" he later said; \"I concede, looking back, that I should have devoted much more time to my school work and less to sport.\"{{sfn|Van Rensburg|1975|p=314}} All the same, his grades were good enough to win a place at [[Rhodes University College]], in [[Grahamstown]] in South Africa, then often attended by Rhodesian students\u2014partly because Rhodesia then had no university of its own, and partly because of the common eponymous association with [[Cecil Rhodes]]. Smith enrolled at the start of 1938, reading for a [[Bachelor of Commerce]] degree.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=42\u201343}} After injuring his knee playing rugby, he took up rowing and became [[Boat positions (sport rowing)|stroke]] for the university crew.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=44}}\n\n===Second World War; Royal Air Force pilot===\n{{main|Military service of Ian Smith}}\n\nWhen the [[Second World War]] broke out in 1939, Southern Rhodesia had had [[self-governing colony|self-government]] for 16 years, having gained [[responsible government]] from the UK in 1923. It was unique in the [[British Empire]] and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] in that it held extensive autonomous powers (including defence, but not foreign affairs) while lacking [[dominion]] status. As a British colony, Southern Rhodesia [[Southern Rhodesia in World War II|entered the conflict]] automatically when Britain declared war on 3 September 1939, but its government issued a symbolic declaration of war anyway.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p= 9}} Smith, who was about halfway through his university course, later described feeling patriotically compelled to put his studies aside to \"fight for Britain and all that it represented\".{{sfn|Smith|1997|p= 10}} Excited by the idea of flying a [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]],{{sfn|Smith|1997|p= 10}} he wanted to join the air force, but was prevented from immediately doing so by a policy adopted in Rhodesia not to recruit university students until after they graduated.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp= 45\u201346}} Smith engineered his recruitment into the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) in spite of this rule during 1940, suppressing mention of his studies,{{sfn|Smith|1997|p= 10}} and formally joined in September 1941.{{sfn|Cowderoy|Nesbit|1987|pp= 13\u201314}}\n\n[[File:Ian Smith RAF 3.jpg|thumb|left|Smith with [[No. 237 Squadron RAF|No. 237 (Rhodesia) Squadron RAF]], {{circa}}&nbsp;1943, in the Second World War's [[Mediterranean and Middle East theatre of World War II|Middle Eastern theatre]]|alt= A man in a Second World War-era Royal Air Force uniform]]\n\nAfter a year's training at Gwelo under the [[British Commonwealth Air Training Plan|Empire Air Training Scheme]],{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp= 47\u201349}} Smith passed out with the rank of [[pilot officer]] in September 1942.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue= 35876 |supp=y|pages= 488\u2013489|date= 26 January 1943}}</ref> He hoped to be stationed in Britain,{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp= 11\u201312}} but was posted to the [[Mediterranean and Middle East theatre of World War II|Middle East]] instead; there he joined [[No. 237 Squadron RAF|No. 237 (Rhodesia) Squadron RAF]], flying [[Hawker Hurricane|Hurricanes]].{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp= 50\u201354}} In October 1943, in Egypt, Smith crashed his Hurricane after his throttle malfunctioned during a dawn takeoff.{{sfn|Van Rensburg|1975|p= 315}} Suffering serious facial disfigurements, he also broke his jaw, leg and shoulder.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp= 50\u201354}} Doctors and surgeons in [[Cairo]] rebuilt Smith's face through [[skin grafting|skin grafts]] and [[plastic surgery]],{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=55}} and he was passed fit to fly again in March 1944.{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp= 11\u201312}} Turning down an offer to return to Rhodesia as an instructor,{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p= 55}} he rejoined No. 237 Squadron, which had switched to flying Spitfire Mk IXs, in [[Corsica]] in May 1944.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=13}}\n\nDuring a [[strafing]] raid over northern Italy on 22 June 1944,{{sfn|Cowderoy|Nesbit|1987|pp= 13\u201314}} enemy flak hit Smith's craft and he had to bail out behind German lines.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp= 56\u201357}} A peasant family named Zunino hid him for a brief time;{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=58\u201359}} he then joined a group of pro-Allied [[Italian resistance movement|Italian partisans]] with whom he took part in sabotage operations against the German garrison for about three months. When the Germans pulled out of the area in October 1944, Smith left to try to link up with the Allied forces who had just [[Operation Dragoon|invaded]] southern France. Accompanied by three other servicemen, each from a different European country, and a local guide, Smith hiked across the [[Maritime Alps]], finishing the journey walking barefoot on the ice and snow. American troops recovered him in November 1944.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=66\u201373}} Smith again turned down the offer of a billet in Rhodesia{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp= 21\u201323}} and returned to active service in April 1945 with [[No. 130 Squadron RAF|No. 130 (Punjab) Squadron]], by then based in western Germany. He flew combat missions there, \"[having] a little bit of fun shooting up odd things\", he recalled, until the [[End of World War II in Europe|war in Europe ended]] on 7 May 1945 with [[German Instrument of Surrender|Germany's surrender]]. Smith remained with No. 130 Squadron for the rest of his service, flying with the unit to Denmark and Norway, and was discharged at the end of 1945 with the rank of [[flight lieutenant]].{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp= 74\u201376}} He retained reasonable proficiency in [[Italian language|Italian]] for the rest of his life, albeit reportedly with an \"atrocious\" accent.{{sfn|After the Battle|1975|p= 45}}\n\n===Graduation, marriage and entrance to politics===\n[[File:College House, Rhodes University.jpg|thumb|College House, the men's residence at [[Rhodes University]], Smith's ''alma mater''|alt=A white building with large windows]]\n\nWith Jock in increasingly poor health after the war, the Smith family briefly considered sending Ian to start a life in the United States with the help of Jock's brother Elijah, who had become a prosperous New York businessman. Smith showed little interest in leaving Rhodesia, however,{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=25}} and decided that he would finish at university, then come home and buy his own farm. He returned to Rhodes University in early 1946 to find the campus swamped with veterans like himself\u2014there were 400 of them out of barely 1,000 students. Smith became spokesman for the university's ex-servicemen, senior student of his hall and chairman of the students' representative council. He turned down the presidency of the rowing club, saying it would be one administrative commitment too many, but agreed to coach the crew. Training the rowers under strict military-style discipline, he led them to victory at the 1946 South African Inter-Varsity Boat Race at the [[Vaal Dam]] south of [[Johannesburg]], upstaging the well-fancied [[University of the Witwatersrand|Wits]] crew, and subsequently received national-standard varsity [[sporting colours|honours]] for rowing, the first Rhodes student ever to do so. At the end of the year, having passed the exams to gain his commerce degree (\"by some miracle\", he recalled), he returned to Southern Rhodesia to study farming at [[Gwebi College of Agriculture|Gwebi Agricultural College]], near Salisbury.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=79\u201380}}\n\nSmith attended dedicated courses for ex-servicemen at Gwebi during 1947 and 1948, learning skills such as ploughing, herding and milking; he gained practical experience at Taylor's dairy farm near Selukwe and on a tobacco ranch at [[Marondera|Marandellas]].{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=80\u201381}} In 1947, he met [[Janet Smith (Rhodesia)|Janet Duvenage]] (''n\u00e9e'' Watt),{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=28\u201329}} a schoolteacher from the [[Cape Province|Cape]] in South Africa who had come to Selukwe to stay with family after the death of her husband [[Piet Duvenage|Piet]] on the rugby field. What Janet had planned as a short holiday for herself and her two infant children, Jean and Robert, turned into a permanent move when she accepted a job offer from the Selukwe junior school.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=81}} Smith later wrote that the qualities that had attracted him most to Janet were her intelligence, courage and \"oppos[ition] on principle to side-stepping or evading an issue&nbsp;... her tendency was to opt for a decision requiring courage, as opposed to taking the easy way out\".{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=28\u201329}} They became engaged in 1948. Meanwhile, Smith negotiated the purchase of a piece of rough land near Selukwe, bounded by the [[Runde River|Lundi]] and Impali Rivers and bisected by a clear stream.{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=28\u201329}} He and Janet gave the previously nameless {{convert|3600|acre|km2|adj=on}} plot the name that the local [[Shona people|Karanga people]] used to refer to the stream, \"Gwenoro\",{{refn|Previously part of the vast Aberfoyle estate, the property was officially called \"Remainder of Subdivision 4 of Aberfoyle Ranch\" when Smith bought it from the Bechuanaland Exploration Company, which had owned it since the late-nineteenth century. \"Gwenoro\" means \"Place of the Kudu\" (''gwe'' meaning \"the place\" and ''noro'' [[kudu]]).{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=28\u201329}}|group=n|name=\"gwenoro\"}} and set up a ranch where they ran cattle and grew tobacco and maize.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=81\u201388}}\n\nA [[1948 Southern Rhodesian general election|general election]] was called in Southern Rhodesia in July 1948 after the [[United Federal Party|United Party]] government, headed by the Prime Minister [[Godfrey Huggins, 1st Viscount Malvern|Sir Godfrey Huggins]], unexpectedly lost a vote in the [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]]. In August, about a month before election day, Smith was approached by members of the opposition [[Southern Rhodesia Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] who asked him to stand for them in Selukwe.{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=29\u201330}} [[Jacob Smit]]'s Liberals, despite their name, were decidedly illiberal, chiefly representing commercial farming, mining and industrial interests.{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=237}} Smith was initially reluctant, saying he was too busy organising his life to stand, but agreed after one of the Liberal officials suggested that a political career might allow him to defend the values he had fought for in the Second World War.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=105\u2013106}} With their wedding barely a fortnight away, Janet was astonished to learn of Smith's decision to run for parliament, having never before heard him discuss politics. \"I can't say that I am really interested in party politics,\" Smith explained to her, \"but I've always been most interested in sound government.\"{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=81\u201382}} Smith duly became a Liberal Party politician, finalised his purchase of Gwenoro, and married Janet, adopting her two children as his own, all in a few weeks in August 1948. They enjoyed a few days' honeymoon at [[Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe|Victoria Falls]], then went straight into the election campaign.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=81\u201382}}\n\nThe Southern Rhodesian electoral system allowed only those who met certain financial and educational qualifications to vote. The criteria were applied equally to all regardless of race, but since most black citizens did not meet the set standards, the electoral roll and the colonial parliament were overwhelmingly white.{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|pp=48\u201353}} Smith canvassed around the geographically very large Selukwe constituency and quickly won considerable popularity. Many white families were receptive to him because of their respect for his father, or because they had had children at school with him. His RAF service also helped, particularly as the local United Party candidate, Petrus Cilliers, had been interned during the hostilities for opposing the war effort.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=108}} On 15 September 1948, Smith defeated Cilliers and the [[Rhodesia Labour Party|Labour]] candidate Egon Klifborg with 361 votes out of 747, and thereby became Member of Parliament for Selukwe.{{sfn|Willson|1963|p=167}} At 29 years old, he was the youngest MP in Southern Rhodesian history.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=109}} The Liberals, however, were roundly defeated, going from 12 seats before the election to only five afterwards. Jacob Smit, who had lost his seat in Salisbury City,{{sfn|Willson|1963|p=167}} retired and was replaced as [[Leader of the Opposition]] by [[Raymond Stockil]], who renamed the Liberals the Rhodesia Party.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=109}} Having grown up in an area of [[Cape Town]] so pro-[[Jan Smuts|Smuts]] that she had never had to vote, Janet did not think her husband's entry to parliament would alter their lives at all. \"First of all I was marrying a farmer,\" she later said, \"now he was going to be a politician as well. So I said, 'Well, if you are really interested in it, carry on.'...&nbsp;It never dawned on me\u2014being so naive about politicians\u2014that our lives would be affected in the slightest degree.\"{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=82}}\n\n==Parliament==\n\n===Backbencher===\n[[File:Southern Rhodesian Legislative Assembly, 1948.jpg|thumb|upright=1.7|The seventh [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Assembly]], the first to feature Smith, in 1948. Smith is the left-most figure in the back row.|alt=A formative photograph of about 30 politicians, standing and sitting in four rows]]\nBecause of Southern Rhodesia's small size and lack of major controversies, its [[unicameralism|unicameral]] parliament then sat only twice a year, for about three months in total, holding discussions in the afternoons either side of a half-hour break for tea on the lawn.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=31}} Smith's early parliamentary commitments in Salisbury therefore did not detract greatly from his ranching. His maiden speech to the Legislative Assembly, in November 1948, concerned the Union of South Africa Trade Agreement Bill, then at its second [[reading (legislature)|reading]]. He was slow to make an impact in parliament\u2014most of his early contributions related to farming and mining\u2014but his exertions within the party won him Stockil's respect and confidence.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=109}} Janet ran Gwenoro during Smith's absences,{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=83}} and gave birth to his only biological child, [[Alec Smith|Alec]], in Gwelo on 20 May 1949.{{sfn|Independent|2006}} Smith also served as a [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]] [[Presbyterian polity#Elder|elder]].{{sfn|DeRoche|2003|p=100}}\n\nThe pursuit of full dominion status was then regarded as something of a non-issue by most Southern Rhodesian politicians. They viewed themselves as virtually independent already; they lacked only the foreign affairs portfolio and taking this on would mean having to shoulder the expense for high commissions and embassies overseas.<ref>{{Harvnb|Smith|1997|p=32}}; {{Harvnb|Berlyn|1978|p=106}}.</ref> Huggins and the United Party instead pursued an initially semi-independent Federation with [[Northern Rhodesia]] and [[Nyasaland]], two protectorates directly administered from London,{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=279}} with the hope of ultimately creating a single, united dominion in south-central Africa.{{refn|The original vision shared by Huggins and his Northern Rhodesian counterpart [[Roy Welensky|Sir Roy Welensky]] was of a [[unitary state|unitary]] amalgamation of the two Rhodesias that would eventually become a dominion. British politicians rejected this idea, asserting that black Northern Rhodesians would never accept it, but agreed to consider a Federation on the condition that neighbouring Nyasaland was also included.{{sfn|Blake|1977|pp=247\u2013249}}|group=n|name=\"fed\"}}\n\nSmith was one of the few to raise the independence issue at this time, according to his memoirs because his \"instinct and training told me to be prepared for every contingency\".{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=32}} During the Federation debate in the House of Assembly, he posited that since Southern Rhodesia was effectively choosing Federation over independence, a clause should be inserted into the bill guaranteeing Southern Rhodesia dominion status in the event of a Federal break-up. The United Party rejected this on the grounds that the Federation had to be declared indissoluble so it could raise loans.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=32}} Smith was uncertain about the Federal project, but publicly supported it after the mostly white electorate approved it in a [[1953 Southern Rhodesian federation referendum|referendum]] in April 1953. He told the ''[[The Herald (Zimbabwe)|Rhodesia Herald]]'' that now it had been decided to pursue Federation, it was in Southern Rhodesia's best interests for everybody to try to make it succeed.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=110}} He and other Rhodesia Party politicians joined the new [[Federal Party (Rhodesia and Nyasaland)|Federal Party]], headed by Huggins and Northern Rhodesia's [[Roy Welensky|Sir Roy Welensky]], on 29 April 1953.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=33}}\n\n===Federation; Chief Whip===\n[[File:Federation rhodesia nyasaland.png|thumb|The three territories of the [[Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland]]|alt=A map. See description]]\nThe [[Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland|Federation]] was overtly led by Southern Rhodesia, the most developed of the three territories\u2014Salisbury was its capital and Huggins its first Prime Minister. [[Garfield Todd]] replaced Huggins as Prime Minister of Southern Rhodesia. Resigning his Selukwe seat, Smith contested and won the Federal Assembly's [[Midlands Province|Midlands]] constituency in the inaugural [[1953 Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland election|Federal election]] on 15 December 1953,{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=33}} and thereafter continued as a [[backbench]] member of little distinction. In the recollection of Welensky, who took over as Federal Prime Minister on Huggins's retirement in 1956, Smith \"didn't spend much time in Salisbury\" during the early Federal period, and had \"three major interests&nbsp;... one was daylight saving, one was European education and he always showed an interest in farming\".{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=111}}\n\nSmith received his first political office in November 1958, following that month's Federal election (in which he was returned as MP for [[Gwanda]]), after one of Welensky's Federal Cabinet ministers requested Smith's appointment as a [[Parliamentary Secretary]] in the new [[United Federal Party]] (UFP) government. Welensky turned this down, saying that while he appreciated Smith's relative seniority on the back benches after 10 years in parliament, he did not think he had \"shown the particular drive that I would have expected\" for such a role.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=111\u2013112}} He decided to instead give Smith \"a run as [[Chief Whip]], which is generally the step to a ministerial appointment, and&nbsp;... see how he works out\".{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=111\u2013112}}\n\nAccording to his biographer Phillippa Berlyn, Smith remained a somewhat pedestrian figure as Chief Whip, though he was acknowledged by his peers as someone who \"did his homework well\" whenever he contributed.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=114}} [[Clifford Dupont]], then Smith's counterpart as Chief Whip of the [[Dominion Party]], later commented that the UFP's huge majority in the Federal Assembly gave Smith little opportunity to distinguish himself as few votes were ever in serious doubt.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=114}}\n\n===Leaving the UFP===\nAmid [[decolonization of Africa|decolonisation]] and the [[Wind of Change (speech)|Wind of Change]], the idea of \"[[no independence before majority rule]]\" (\"NIBMAR\") gained considerable ground in British political circles during the late 1950s and early 1960s. The Federation, which had faced black opposition from the start, particularly in Northern Rhodesia and Nyasaland, grew ever more tenuous.<ref>{{Harvnb|Jackson|1990|pp=96\u201397}}; {{Harvnb|Wood|2005|p=20}}.</ref> Despite Todd's lowering of Southern Rhodesia's educational and financial voting qualifications in 1957 to enlarge the black electorate, very few of the newly enfranchised blacks registered to vote, partly because the black nationalist movement targeted those who did with arson attacks and [[Molotov cocktail|petrol bombings]].{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=95\u201396, 111\u2013120}}{{refn|The movement's leaders had decided that black nationalists should boycott constitutional politics, contending that majority rule could be achieved fastest through non-co-operation, violence and overseas activism.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=125}} |group=n|name=\"boycott\"}} Attempting to advance the case for Southern Rhodesian independence, particularly in the event of Federal dissolution,{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=15\u201316}} [[Edgar Whitehead|Sir Edgar Whitehead]], who replaced Todd in 1958, agreed to a new constitution with Britain in 1961.{{sfn|Rowland|1978|pp=249\u2013250}} The 1961 constitution contained no explicit independence guarantees, but Whitehead, Welensky and other proponents nevertheless presented it to the Southern Rhodesian electorate as the \"independence constitution\" under which Southern Rhodesia would become a [[Commonwealth realm]] on a par with Australia, Canada and New Zealand if the Federation broke up.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=89}}\n\nSmith was one of the loudest voices of white dissent against the new constitution. He opposed its splitting of the heretofore non-racial, qualified electorate into graduated \"A\" and \"B\" rolls, saying the proposed system had \"racialist\" connotations,{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=124}} and objected to the idea that the first black MPs would be elected on what he said would be a \"debased franchise\".{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=79}}{{refn|The electoral system devised in the 1961 constitution replaced the common voters' roll with two rolls, the \"A\" roll and the \"B\" roll, the latter of which had lower qualifications intended to make it easier for prospective voters to enter the political system. There were 50 \"A\"-roll constituencies and 15 larger \"B\"-roll districts, with a complicated mechanism of \"cross-voting\" allowing \"B\"-roll voters to slightly influence \"A\"-roll elections and vice versa. This system was theoretically non-racial, but in practice the \"A\" roll was largely white and the \"B\" roll was almost all black.{{sfn|Palley|1966|pp=414\u2013416}}|group=n|name=\"1961franchise\"}} \"Our policy in the past has always been that we would have a government, in Rhodesia, based on merit and that people wouldn't worry whether you were black or whether you were white,\" he said.{{sfn|Van Rensburg|1975|p=316}} He also pointed out that the document did not actually guarantee Southern Rhodesian independence in the event of Federal dissolution.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=74}} At the UFP vote on the constitution on 22 February 1961, Smith was the only member out of 280 to vote against it.{{refn|He later claimed that \"between 60 and 70\" UFP members voted in favour having told him beforehand that they would vote against. According to the historian J&nbsp;R&nbsp;T Wood, many of these later apologised to Smith.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=79}}|group=n|name=\"vote\"}} Deeply disillusioned by these developments, he resigned from the UFP soon after to sit in the Federal Assembly as an [[Independent (politician)|independent]]. He lent his support to the \"United Group\", an awkward coalition wherein [[Winston Field]]'s conservative Dominion Party closed ranks with [[Robert Clarkson Tredgold|Sir Robert Tredgold]] and other liberals against the constitutional proposals, despite opposing them for totally contradictory reasons.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=89}} The black nationalist leaders initially endorsed the constitution, signing the draft document, but almost immediately repudiated it and called for blacks to boycott elections held under it.<ref>{{Harvnb|Blake|1977|pp=334\u2013335}}; {{Harvnb|Wood|2005|pp=74\u201375}}.</ref> A [[1961 Southern Rhodesian constitution referendum|referendum]] of the mostly white electorate approved the new constitution by a majority of 65% on 26 July 1961.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=92}}\n\n===Forming the Rhodesian Front===\nAs the UK government granted majority rule in Nyasaland and made moves towards the same in Northern Rhodesia, Smith decided that the Federation was a lost cause and resolved to found a new party that would push for Southern Rhodesian independence without an immediate transfer of power. With the support of the millionaire rancher, miner and industrialist [[Boss Lilford|D&nbsp;C \"Boss\" Lilford]], he formed the Rhodesian Reform Party (RRP), based around defectors from the UFP, in December 1961.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=97}} Meanwhile, Whitehead attempted to counter the black nationalists and persuade newly eligible blacks to register as voters. He banned the main nationalist group, the National Democratic Party, for being violent and intimidatory\u2014it reformed overnight as the [[Zimbabwe African People's Union]] (ZAPU){{refn|The black nationalist movement had adopted Zimbabwe, derived from the [[Shona people|Shona]] name for the ancient ruined city [[Great Zimbabwe]], around 1960 as the name they would give Southern Rhodesia under majority rule.<ref>{{Harvnb|Fontein|2006|pp=119\u2013120}}; {{Harvnb|Ndlovu-Gatsheni|2009|pp=72, 113\u2013114}}.</ref> The National Democratic Party had been founded in 1960 to succeed the [[Southern Rhodesia African National Congress]], which dated back to 1957.{{sfn|Ndlovu-Gatsheni|2009|pp=73, 112}}|group=n|name=\"zimbabwe\"}}\u2014and announced that the UFP would repeal the Land Apportionment Act, which segregated the ownership and occupation of certain areas on a racial basis, if it won the next Southern Rhodesian election.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=98}} Commitments such as these won the UFP few black votes and prompted many scandalised whites to defect to the RRP or Field's Dominion Party.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=98\u201399}}\n\nSmith, Field and others met in Salisbury on 13 March 1962 and agreed to unite against Whitehead as the [[Rhodesian Front]] (RF). The Front ranged from former UFP men, including Smith, who advocated gradual transition and a government based on merit and electoral qualifications, to the Dominion Party's more right-wing members, some of whom held segregationist views not dissimilar to those of South Africa's [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]]. Amid these differences, the nascent RF coalition was shaky at best. Its members were brought together by their common opposition to Whitehead's promises of fast-track reform, which they agreed would lead to a [[Congo Crisis|Congo]]-style national crisis, the flight of the white community and ultimately the country's destruction.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=100\u2013101}} In the wider [[Cold War]] context, the ardently anti-communist RF aspired to represent a pro-[[Western Bloc|Western]] bulwark in Africa, alongside South Africa and Portugal, in the face of what they saw as Soviet and Chinese expansionism.{{sfn|Olson|Shadle|1996|pp=1029\u20131030}} Smith asserted that the RF worked to thwart \"this mad idea of a hand-over, of a sell-out of the European and his civilisation, indeed of everything he had put into his country\".{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=100\u2013101}} \"The white man is the master of Rhodesia,\" he said; \"[he] has built it and intends to keep it\".{{sfn|Time|1964}}\n\nThe RF ignored the April 1962 Federal elections, deeming them irrelevant, and instead concentrated on the Southern Rhodesian elections that were due at the end of the year.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=100\u2013101}} Whitehead attempted to curb the continuing black nationalist violence through new legislation and in September 1962 banned ZAPU, arresting 1,094 of its members and describing it as a \"terrorist organisation\",{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=116\u2013117}} but he was still seen by much of the electorate as too liberal. He set a [[1962 Southern Rhodesian general election|general election]] for 14 December 1962. A number of corporations that had previously funded UFP campaigning this time backed the RF. The RF campaign exploited the chaos in the Congo and the uncertainty regarding Southern Rhodesia's future to create a theme of urgency\u2014it pledged to keep power \"in responsible hands\", to defend the Land Apportionment Act, to oppose compulsory integration, and to win Southern Rhodesian independence.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=119\u2013121}}\n\nThe electoral race was close-run until the night before election day, when Whitehead made what proved a fatal political gaffe by telling a public meeting at Marandellas that he would appoint a black Cabinet minister immediately if he won the election, and might soon have as many as six. This statement appeared on the radio news just before the polling booths opened the next morning, and stunned white voters. Many abandoned Whitehead at the last minute.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=121}} The results, announced on 15 December 1962, put the RF into government with 35 \"A\"-roll seats to the UFP's 15 \"A\"-roll and 14 \"B\"-roll seats.{{refn|The remaining \"B\"-roll seat was won by [[Ahrn Palley]], a liberal white independent who generally opposed the RF. The Field government thus had a working majority of five seats.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=121}}|group=n|name=\"palley\"}} Few had expected this; even the RF was somewhat taken aback by its victory,{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=122}} though Smith later described feeling \"quietly confident\" on election day.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=47}} Contesting the Umzingwane constituency in the rural south-west, he bested the UFP's Reginald Segar by 803 votes to 546.{{sfn|Willson|1963|p=203}}\n\n===Deputy Prime Minister under Field===\nAnnouncing his Cabinet on 17 December 1962, Field named Smith his Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of the Treasury.{{sfn|Van Rensburg|1975|p=316}} Two days later, [[Rab Butler|R&nbsp;A Butler]], the UK's Deputy Prime Minister and [[First Secretary of State]], announced that the UK government would allow Nyasaland to leave the Federation.{{refn|This decision was far from new; [[Hastings Banda]], the black nationalist leader in Nyasaland, had been secretly informed of it ten months before.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=99}}|group=n|name=\"decision\"}} With Northern Rhodesia now also under a secessionist black nationalist government\u2014[[Kenneth Kaunda]] and [[Harry Nkumbula]] had formed a coalition to keep the UFP out\u2014and Southern Rhodesia under the RF, the Federation was effectively over.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=122\u2013124}} The Field Cabinet made Southern Rhodesian independence on Federal dissolution its first priority,{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=122\u2013124}} but the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government in the UK was reluctant to grant this under the 1961 constitution as it knew doing so would lead to censure and loss of prestige in the United Nations (UN) and the Commonwealth.{{sfn|McWilliam|2003}} Indeed, Southern Rhodesia's minority government had already become something of an embarrassment to the UK and it hurt Britain's reputation to even maintain the ''status quo'' there.{{sfn|Nelson|1983|p=43}} Granting independence without major constitutional reform would furthermore provoke outcry from the Conservatives' main parliamentary opposition, the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], which was strongly anti-colonial and supportive of black nationalist ambitions.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=242}}\n\n[[File:Victoria Falls Hotel.jpg|thumb|The [[Victoria Falls Hotel]], where the Federal break-up conference was held in 1963|alt=A large, white colonial-style hotel]]\nButler announced on 6 March 1963 that he was going to convene a conference to decide the Federation's future. It would be impossible (or at least very difficult) for the UK to dissolve the union without Southern Rhodesia's co-operation as the latter, being self-governing, had been co-signatory to the Federal agreement in 1953.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=133\u2013135}} According to Smith, Field, Dupont and other RF politicians, Butler made several oral independence guarantees to ensure Southern Rhodesia's attendance and support at the conference, but repeatedly refused to give anything on paper.{{refn|In particular, Field and Smith claimed that Butler told them at [[Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe|Victoria Falls]] on 27 June 1963 that in return for their help in winding up the Federation, Southern Rhodesia would be granted \"independence no later than, if not before, the other two territories&nbsp;... in view of your country's wonderful record of Responsible Government over the past forty years&nbsp;... and above all the great loyalty you have always given to Britain in time of war\".<ref name=butler>{{Harvnb|Wood|2005|pp=138\u2013140, 167}}; {{Harvnb|Berlyn|1978|p=135}}; {{Harvnb|Smith|1997|pp=51\u201352}}.</ref>|group=n|name=\"promise\"}} Field and Smith claimed that Butler justified this to them the day before the conference began by saying that binding [[Government of the United Kingdom|Whitehall]] to a document rather than his word would be against the Commonwealth's \"spirit of trust\"\u2014an argument that Field eventually accepted. \"Let's remember the trust you emphasised,\" Smith warned, according to Field's account wagging his finger at Butler; \"if you break that you will live to regret it.\"{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=167}} No minutes were made of this meeting. Butler denied afterwards that he had ever made such a promise.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=167}} Southern Rhodesia attended the conference, held at the [[Victoria Falls Hotel]] over a week starting from 28 June 1963, and among other things it was agreed to formally liquidate the Federation at the end of 1963.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=169\u2013172}}\n\nThe Federation dissolved on 31 December 1963 with Nyasaland and Northern Rhodesia both on track for full statehood by the end of 1964, while Southern Rhodesia continued to drift in uncertainty. Under huge pressure from the RF to rectify this matter and win independence, Field's perceived vacillation and timidness in his dealings with the UK government caused sections of his party to lose confidence in him during early 1964.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=189\u2013190}} On 2 April 1964, with Smith in the chair, the RF caucus passed a near-unanimous [[motion of no confidence|vote of no confidence]] in Field, leading to the Prime Minister's resignation 11 days later. Smith accepted the Cabinet's nomination to take his place.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=204\u2013207}} He was the first Southern Rhodesian Prime Minister to have been born in the country,{{refn|Welensky was also born in Southern Rhodesia. Of the seven previous Southern Rhodesian Prime Ministers, three had been born in Britain; the others had been born in South Africa, [[Bechuanaland Protectorate|Bechuanaland]], New Zealand and the British Embassy in Germany.<ref>{{Harvnb|Baxter|Burke|1970|pp=125, 340}}; {{Harvnb|Schwarz|2011|p=411}}; {{Harvnb|Wood|2005|p=12}}.</ref>|group=n|name=\"nativeborn\"}} something that he thought profoundly altered the character of the dispute with Britain. \"For the first time in its history the country now had a Rhodesian-born PM, someone whose roots were not in Britain, but in southern Africa,\" he later reflected\u2014\"in other words, a white African.\"{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=67}}\n\n==Prime Minister==\n\n===First days; banning of PCC/ZAPU and ZANU===\nMost of the Southern Rhodesian press predicted that Smith would not last long; one column called him \"a momentary man\", thrust into the spotlight by the RF's dearth of proven leaders. His only real rival to replace Field had been [[William John Harper|William Harper]], an ardent segregationist who had headed the Dominion Party's Southern Rhodesian branch during the Federal years.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=209\u2013210}} Some reporters predicted Welensky's imminent introduction to Southern Rhodesian politics at the head of an RF\u2013UFP [[coalition government]], but Welensky showed little interest in this idea, saying he would be unable to manoeuvre in an RF-dominated House.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=209}} The RF's replacement of Field with Smith drew criticism from the British Labour leader [[Harold Wilson]], who called it \"brutal\",{{sfn|Wilson|1974|p=48}} while [[John Baines Johnston|J&nbsp;B Johnston]], the British High Commissioner in Salisbury, indicated his disapproval by refusing to meet Smith for two weeks after he took office.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=209}} The ZAPU leader [[Joshua Nkomo]] branded the new Smith Cabinet \"a suicide squad&nbsp;... interested not in the welfare of all the people but only in their own\", and predicted that the RF would \"eventually destroy themselves\".{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=208}} Asserting that a lasting \"place for the white man\" in Southern Rhodesia would benefit all of the country's people, the new Prime Minister said the government should be based \"on merit, not on colour or nationalism\",{{sfn|Hall|1966|pp=22, 30}} and insisted that there would be \"no African nationalist government here in my lifetime\".{{sfn|Hall|1966|p=26}}\n\nSmith announced his Cabinet on his first day in office, 14 April 1964. He increased the number of ministers from 10 to 11, redistributed portfolios, and made three new appointments.{{refn|These were [[Arthur Philip Smith|A&nbsp;P Smith]] (no relation) as Minister of Education, [[Harry Reedman]] as Minister of Roads, Immigration and Tourism, and [[Phillip van Heerden]] as Minister of Mines, Land and Water Development.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=209\u2013210}}|group=n|name=\"new64\"}} Smith's fellow former UFP men made up most of the new RF Cabinet, with Harper and the Minister of Agriculture, the [[James Graham, 7th Duke of Montrose|Duke of Montrose]] (also called Lord Graham), heading a minority of hardline Dominion Party veterans. [[Ken Flower]], whom Field had appointed Director of the [[Central Intelligence Organisation]] (CIO) on its creation the previous year, was surprised to be retained by Smith.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=209\u2013210}} Smith announced his policies to the nation through full-page advertisements in the newspapers: \"No forced integration. No lowering of standards. No abdication of responsible government. No repeal of the Land Apportionment Act. No appeasement to suit the [[Bandung Conference|Afro-Asian bloc]].\"{{sfn|Van Rensburg|1975|p=317}} \"An honest Rhodesian,\" a 1964 political poster declared\u2014\"Trust Mr Smith. He will never hand over Rhodesia.\"{{sfn|Cowell|2007 a}} Smith retained the post of Minister of External Affairs to himself.<ref name=\"rhodesian_offices_1924_1964\">http://ir.uz.ac.zw/jspui/bitstream/10646/3684/1/Willson_Holders_of_Administrative_and_Ministerial_office_1894_1964.pdf</ref>\n\nOne of the Smith government's first actions was to crack down hard on the black nationalist political violence that had erupted following the establishment of a second black nationalist organisation, the [[Zimbabwe African National Union]] (ZANU), by disgruntled ZAPU members in Tanzania in August 1963.{{refn|[[Dar es Salaam]], Tanzania was then ZAPU's main base of operations.{{sfn|Martin|Johnson|1981|p=70}}|group=n|name=\"zanu63\"}} The rival movements were split tribally, ZAPU being mostly [[Northern Ndebele people|Ndebele]] and ZANU predominantly [[Shona people|Shona]], and politically\u2014ZAPU, which had relabelled itself the People's Caretaker Council (PCC) within Southern Rhodesia to circumvent its ban, was [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] and backed by the [[Warsaw Pact]] and its allies, while ZANU had aligned itself with [[Maoism]] and the bloc headed by communist China.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=173\u2013174}} Their respective supporters in the black townships clashed constantly, also targeting non-aligned blacks whom they hoped to recruit, and sporadically attacked whites, businesses and police stations.<ref>{{Harvnb|Martin|Johnson|1981|pp=70\u201371}}; {{Harvnb|Wood|2005|p=211}}.</ref>\n\nAmid PCC/ZAPU's calls for various strikes and protests, including an appeal for black children to boycott state schools, Smith's Justice Minister Clifford Dupont had Nkomo and other PCC/ZAPU leaders restricted at [[Gonakudzingwa Restriction Camp|Gonakudzingwa]] in the remote south-east two days after Smith took office.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=211}} The politically motivated killing of a white man, [[Death of Petrus Oberholzer|Petrus Oberholzer]], near [[Chimanimani|Melsetter]] by ZANU insurgents on 4 July 1964 marked the start of intensified black nationalist violence and police counteraction that culminated in the banning of ZANU and PCC/ZAPU on 26 August, with most of the two movements' respective leaders concurrently jailed or restricted.<ref>{{Harvnb|Cilliers|1984|p=5}}; {{Harvnb|Martin|Johnson|1981|pp=70\u201371}}; {{Harvnb|Ranger|1997|p=237}}; {{Harvnb|Wood|2005|pp=220\u2013228}}.</ref> ZANU, ZAPU and their respective guerrilla armies\u2014the [[Zimbabwe African National Liberation Army]] (ZANLA) and the [[Zimbabwe People's Revolutionary Army]] (ZIPRA)\u2014thereafter operated from abroad.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=228}}\n\n===Unilateral Declaration of Independence (UDI)===\n{{main|Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence}}\n\nSmith, who had been to the UK only four times before 1964 and never more than briefly, was soon labelled a \"raw colonial\" by Whitehall.{{sfn|Caute|1983|p=89}} He was almost immediately at loggerheads with the UK government, which he claimed had forsaken British ideals, and the Commonwealth, which he said had abandoned its own founding principles amid the Wind of Change. He accused both of isolating Southern Rhodesia because it still respected these values.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=216\u2013217}} When he learned in June that Salisbury would not be represented at the [[Commonwealth Prime Ministers' Conference]] for the first time since [[British Empire Economic Conference|1932]], he was deeply insulted and alleged British betrayal, double standards and appeasement.{{refn|The Federal Prime Minister had attended instead of his Southern Rhodesian counterpart from 1953 to 1963. Smith had presumed Southern Rhodesia would get its old seat back following Federal dissolution.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=212}}|group=n|name=\"oldseatback\"}} Three months later, Smith accepted the British condition that the independence terms had to be acceptable to majority opinion, but impasse immediately developed regarding the mechanism by which black views would be gauged.{{refn|Smith proposed to measure white and urban black opinion through a general referendum of registered voters, and rural black views through a national ''[[indaba]]'' (tribal conference) of chiefs and headmen. This was turned down by the UK Prime Minister [[Alec Douglas-Home|Sir Alec Douglas-Home]], who said that this satisfied him personally, but would not be accepted by Labour or the international community.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=231\u2013233}}|group=n|name=\"indaba\"}} Labour's narrow victory in the October 1964 UK [[1964 United Kingdom general election|general election]] meant that Smith would be negotiating not with [[Alec Douglas-Home|Sir Alec Douglas-Home]] but with Harold Wilson, who was far less accommodating towards the RF stand.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=241}} Smith declared acceptability to majority opinion to have been demonstrated after a largely white [[1964 Southern Rhodesian independence referendum|referendum]] and an ''[[indaba]]'' of tribal chiefs and headmen both decisively backed independence under the 1961 constitution in October and November 1964,{{refn|The referendum supported by 89% and the 622 tribal leaders did so unanimously.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=246, 249}}|group=n|name=\"results\"}} but black nationalists and the UK government dismissed the ''indaba'' as insufficiently representative of the black community.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=251}}\n\n[[File:Harold Wilson, Den Haag 27-02-1967.jpg|thumb|upright|UK Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]], who took office in October 1964, proved a formidable opponent of Smith.|alt=A photograph of Harold Wilson]]\nFollowing Northern Rhodesia's independence as Zambia in October 1964\u2014Nyasaland had been independent Malawi since July\u2014Southern Rhodesia began referring to itself simply as Rhodesia, but Whitehall rejected this change.{{refn|Legislation passed at Salisbury to shorten the name was ruled ''[[ultra vires]]'' by Whitehall on the grounds that the country's name had been defined in British acts passed at Westminster. Salisbury went on using the shortened name anyway,{{sfn|Palley|1966|pp=742\u2013743}} while the UK government, the United Nations and other overseas bodies continued referring to the country as Southern Rhodesia. This situation continued throughout the UDI period.{{sfn|Rowland|1978|p=251}}|group=n|name=\"name2\"}} Perceiving Smith to be on the verge of a [[unilateral declaration of independence]] (UDI), Wilson issued a statement in October 1964 warning of dire economic and political consequences, and wrote to Smith demanding \"a categorical assurance forthwith\" that no UDI would be attempted. Smith ignored this, expressing confusion as to what he had done to provoke it.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=243\u2013246}} The UK and Rhodesian governments exchanged often confrontational correspondence over the next year or so, each accusing the other of being unreasonable and intransigent.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=257\u2013258}} Little progress was made when two Prime Ministers met in person in January 1965, when Smith travelled to London for [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]]'s funeral.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=271\u2013272}} The RF called a fresh election for [[1965 Rhodesian general election|May 1965]] and, campaigning on an [[election promise]] of independence, won all 50 \"A\"-roll seats (elected mostly by whites).{{refn|The RF won 22 of its 50 seats unopposed. The United People's Party, headed by [[Josiah Gondo]], won 10 of the 15 \"B\"-roll seats, while the rest were won by independents. Gondo became Rhodesia's first black Leader of the Opposition.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=311, 314\u2013315}}|group=n|name=\"gondo\"}} Wilson's ministers deliberately stonewalled Smith during mid-1965, hoping to eventually break him down, but this only caused the Rhodesian hierarchy to feel yet more alienated.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=335}} From June, a peripheral dispute concerned Rhodesia's unilateral and ultimately successful attempt to open an independent [[Rhodesian mission in Lisbon|mission in Lisbon]]; Portugal's acceptance of this in September 1965 prompted British outrage and Rhodesian delight.{{sfn|Fedorowich|Thomas|2001|pp=185\u2013186}}\n\nAmid rumours that UDI was imminent, Smith arrived in London on 4 October 1965 with the declared intent of settling the independence issue,{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=360\u2013363, 367}} but flew home eight days later with the matter unresolved.{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=387\u2013388}} When Wilson travelled to Salisbury on 26 October, Smith offered to enfranchise about half a million black Rhodesians immediately along the lines of \"one taxpayer, one vote\" in return for independence,{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=411\u2013414}} but Wilson said this was unacceptable as most blacks would still be excluded. He proposed a Royal Commission to test public opinion in Rhodesia regarding independence under the 1961 constitution, and suggested that the UK might safeguard black representation in the Rhodesian parliament by withdrawing relevant devolved powers. This latter prospect horrified Smith's team as it seemed to them to have ruled out the failsafe option of keeping the ''status quo''. After Wilson returned to Britain on 30 October 1965,{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=440\u2013443}} he presented terms for the Royal Commission that the Rhodesians found unacceptable\u2014among other things, Britain would not commit itself to accepting the results. Smith rejected these conditions on 5 November, saying they made the whole exercise pointless.{{sfn|Young|1969|p=271}} After waiting a few days for new terms from Wilson,{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=463\u2013467}} Smith made a [[Consensus decision-making|consensus decision]] with his Cabinet to break ties unilaterally on 11 November 1965, and signed the [[Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence|Unilateral Declaration of Independence]] at 11:00 [[Central Africa Time|local time]].{{sfn|Wood|2005|pp=463, 468\u2013471}}\n\n===Fallout from UDI===\nUDI, while received calmly by most Rhodesians, prompted political outrage in the UK and overseas.{{sfn|Wood|2008|pp=3\u20134}} It astonished Wilson, who called on the people of Rhodesia to ignore the post-UDI government, which he described as \"hell-bent on illegal self-destroying\".{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=5}} Following orders from Whitehall and the passage of the [[Southern Rhodesia Act 1965]], the colonial [[Governor of Southern Rhodesia|Governor]] [[Humphrey Gibbs|Sir Humphrey Gibbs]] formally sacked Smith and his Cabinet, accusing them of treason. Smith and his ministers ignored this, considering Gibbs's office obsolete under the 1965 constitution enacted as part of UDI.{{sfn|Wood|2008|pp=3\u20134}}{{refn|This was an independence-style variation on the 1961 constitution with references to British ties removed.{{sfn|Wood|2005|p=471}}|group=n|name=\"1965con\"}} After Gibbs made clear that he would not resign, Smith's government effectively replaced him with Dupont, who was appointed to the post of \"[[Officer Administering the Government]]\" (created by the 1965 constitution). No attempt was made to remove Gibbs from his official residence at Government House, however; he remained there, ignored by the Smith administration, until the declaration of a republic in 1970.{{sfn|Wood|1999}}\n\nSmith and his government initially continued to profess loyalty to Queen Elizabeth II. The 1965 Constitution reconstituted Rhodesia as a Commonwealth realm, with Elizabeth II as \"Queen of Rhodesia\". Indeed, the UDI document ended with the words \"God Save The Queen\". In December 1965, Smith, attempting to assert the rights he claimed as Her Majesty's Rhodesian prime minister, wrote a letter to Elizabeth asking her to appoint Dupont as [[governor-general|Governor-General]] of Rhodesia.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Z8kwAQAAIAAJ&q=%22personal+letter+to+the+Queen,+asking+her+to+accept+Mr+Clifford+Dupont+as+the+new+Governor-General%22&dq=%22personal+letter+to+the+Queen,+asking+her+to+accept+Mr+Clifford+Dupont+as+the+new+Governor-General%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiw87yMrK_WAhUqL8AKHXYYAEsQ6AEIKDAA ''The New Law Journal''], Volume 127, Butterworth, 1978, page 529</ref> The Queen rejected Smith's letter, which she characterised in her response as \"purported advice\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eewqAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Her+Majesty+is+not+able+to+entertain+purported+advice+of+this+kind%22&dq=%22Her+Majesty+is+not+able+to+entertain+purported+advice+of+this+kind%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjlq_bfrq_WAhUWOsAKHQaCCK0Q6AEILDAB ''The International and Comparative Law Quarterly''], Volume 20, page 659, 1971</ref> The UK, with the near-unanimous support of the international community, maintained that Gibbs was now Elizabeth II's only legitimate representative in what it still reckoned as the colony of Southern Rhodesia, and hence the sole lawful authority there.{{sfn|Wood|1999}}\n\nThe [[United Nations General Assembly|UN General Assembly]] and [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]] quickly joined the UK in condemning UDI as illegal and racist. Security Council [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 216|Resolutions 216]] and [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 217|217]], adopted in the days following Smith's declaration, denounced UDI as an illegitimate \"usurpation of power by a racist settler minority\", and called on nations not to entertain diplomatic or economic relations.{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|pp=183\u2013185}} No country recognised Rhodesia as independent.{{sfn|Strack|1978|pp=51\u201352}} Black nationalists in Rhodesia and their overseas backers, prominently the [[Organisation of African Unity]] (OAU), clamoured for the UK to remove Smith's government with a military invasion, but Britain dismissed this option, citing logistical issues, the risk of provoking a pre-emptive Rhodesian strike on Zambia, and the psychological issues likely to accompany any confrontation between British and Rhodesian troops.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=6}} Wilson instead resolved to end UDI through economic sanctions, banning the supply of oil to Rhodesia and the import of most Rhodesian goods to Britain. When Smith continued to receive oil through South Africa and [[Portuguese Mozambique]], Wilson posted a [[Royal Navy]] squadron to the [[Mozambique Channel]] in March 1966. This blockade, the [[Beira Patrol]], was endorsed by [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 221|UN Security Council Resolution 221]] the following month.{{sfn|Mobley|2002|pp=66, 71\u201376, 83}}\n\nWilson predicted in January 1966 that the various boycotts would force Smith to give in \"within a matter of weeks rather than months\",{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=47}} but the British (and later UN) sanctions had little effect on Rhodesia, largely because South Africa and Portugal went on trading with it, providing it with oil and other key resources.{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|p=442}} Clandestine trade with other nations also continued, initially at a reduced level, and the diminished presence of foreign competitors helped domestic industries to slowly mature and expand.{{sfn|Rowe|2001|pp=124\u2013130}} Even many OAU states, while bombarding Rhodesia with opprobrium, continued importing Rhodesian food and other products.{{sfn|Moorcraft|McLaughlin|2008|p=120}} Rhodesia thus avoided the economic cataclysm predicted by Wilson and gradually became more self-sufficient.{{sfn|Rowe|2001|pp=124\u2013130}} \"Rhodesia can not only take it, but she can also make it,\" Smith said on 29 April 1966, while opening the annual Central African Trade Fair in [[Bulawayo]]. \"When I say take it, I use it in two ways. Firstly, when it comes to sanctions we have proved we can take it. Secondly, when it comes to independence, we have also proved we can take it.\"{{sfn|Bolze|Ravn|1966|p=86}}\n\n===''Tiger'' and ''Fearless'' talks with Wilson===\n[[File:Rock of Gibraltar South View.jpg|thumb|[[Gibraltar]], the venue for talks between Smith and Wilson in 1966 and 1968|alt=The Rock of Gibraltar, seen from the sea]]\nWilson told the UK's [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in January 1966 that he would not enter any kind of dialogue with Smith's post-UDI government (which he called \"the illegal regime\") until it gave up its claim of independence,{{sfn|Windrich|1978|p=76}} but by mid-1966 British and Rhodesian civil servants were holding \"talks about talks\" in London and Salisbury.{{sfn|Windrich|1978|p=87}} By November that year, Wilson had agreed to negotiate personally with Smith.{{sfn|Windrich|1978|p=98}} Smith and Wilson subsequently held two rounds of direct negotiations, both of which were held aboard Royal Navy ships off [[Gibraltar]]. The first took place aboard [[HMS Tiger (C20)|HMS ''Tiger'']] between 2 and 4 December 1966,{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=223}} while the second, aboard [[HMS Fearless (L10)|HMS ''Fearless'']], was held between 8 and 13 October 1968.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=535}}\n\nThe UK's prime minister went to HMS ''Tiger'' in a belligerent mindset. Wilson's political secretary [[Marcia Falkender, Baroness Falkender|Marcia Falkender]] later wrote of \"apartheid&nbsp;... on that ship\",{{sfn|Falkender|1972|p=172}} with the British and Rhodesian delegations separated in all activities outside the conference room at Wilson's orders.{{refn|Intending to underline the UK government's opinion of Smith and his delegation as unconstitutional rebels, Wilson officially greeted Gibbs, but denied any formal welcome to Smith. The UK's ministers and officials received the best cabins while the Rhodesians were assigned [[petty officer]]s' quarters.{{sfn|Wood|2008|pp=222\u2013223}}|group=n|name=\"quarters\"}} Despite the uneasy atmosphere\u2014accounts from both sides describe Wilson dealing with the Rhodesians extremely tersely<ref>{{Harvnb|Berlyn|1978|p=175}}; {{Harvnb|Falkender|1972|p=168}}.</ref>\u2014talks progressed relatively smoothly until the subject turned to the manner of the transition. Wilson insisted on the abandonment of the 1965 constitution, the dissolution of the post-UDI government in favour of a \"broad-based\" multiracial interim administration and a period under a British Governor, conditions that Smith saw as tantamount to surrender, particularly as the UK proposed to draft and introduce the new constitution only after a fresh test of opinion under UK control. When Smith asserted on 3 December that he could not settle without first consulting his Cabinet in Salisbury, Wilson was enraged, declaring that a central condition of the summit had been that he and Smith would have [[plenipotentiary]] powers to make a deal.{{sfn|Wood|2008|pp=229\u2013231}}{{refn|Smith disputed this at the time, but later admitted that he could have settled in a plenipotentiary capacity had he found the conditions acceptable.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=177}}|group=n|name=\"tiger\"}} According to J&nbsp;R&nbsp;T Wood, Wilson and his [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] [[Frederick Elwyn Jones, Baron Elwyn-Jones|Sir Elwyn Jones]] then \"bullied Smith for two long days\" to try to get him to settle, without success.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=242}}\n\nA working document was ultimately produced and signed by Smith, Wilson and Gibbs, to be accepted or rejected in its entirety by each Cabinet after the Prime Ministers returned home. Whitehall accepted the proposals, but Salisbury turned them down; Smith announced on 5 December 1966 that while he and his ministers were largely satisfied with the terms, the Cabinet did not feel it could responsibly abandon the 1965 constitution while so much uncertainty surrounded the transition and the new \"mythical constitution yet to be evolved\".{{sfn|Wood|2008|pp=243\u2013246}} Rhodesia's Leader of the Opposition [[Josiah Gondo]] promptly demanded Smith's resignation, reasoning that the Cabinet's rejection of the working document he had helped to draft amounted to a vote of no confidence. The RF ignored him.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=253}} Warning that \"grave actions must follow\",{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=253}} Wilson took the Rhodesia problem to the United Nations, which proceeded to institute the first mandatory trade sanctions in its history with [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 232|Security Council Resolutions 232]] (December 1966) and [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 253|253]] (April 1968). These measures required UN member states to prevent all trade and economic links with Rhodesia.{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|pp=18, 701}}\n\n[[File:HMS Fearless L10 Portsmouth 1994.jpeg|thumb|left|[[HMS Fearless (L10)|HMS ''Fearless'']], the [[Royal Navy]] ship that hosted the 1968 Anglo-Rhodesian summit off Gibraltar|alt=A modern military ship flying the Union Jack]]\nState press censorship, introduced by the Smith administration on UDI, was lifted in early April 1968,{{sfn|Wood|2008|pp=444\u2013445}} though according to the ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|Glasgow Herald]]'' the government retained \"considerable powers to control information. It may reflect no more than Mr Smith's growing confidence that nothing\u2014short of a sell-out to Britain\u2014can undermine his position in Rhodesia\".{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=193}} The series of Rhodesian High Court cases debating the legality of UDI came to a close five months later on 13 September. A panel of judges headed by [[Hugh Beadle|Sir Hugh Beadle]] ruled UDI, the 1965 constitution and Smith's government to be ''de jure'',{{refn|This decision was based on [[Hugo Grotius]]'s assertion that \"the purpose of governing and the purpose of destroying cannot subsist together\"; the judges ruled that the UK could not claim to be governing Rhodesia while it was also applying economic sanctions. Beadle's panel also considered the UK to have acted illegally by involving the UN, arguing that if UDI were illegal, then Rhodesia should have been handled as a domestic issue.{{sfn|Young|1969|pp=538\u2013541}}|group=n|name=\"ruling\"}} prompting the UK Commonwealth Secretary [[George Thomson, Baron Thomson of Monifieth|George Thomson]] to accuse them of breaching \"the fundamental laws of the land\".{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=513}}\n\nOn HMS ''Fearless'', the UK reversed its confrontational approach of the ''Tiger'' talks and made a marked effort to appear genial and welcoming, mixing socially with the Rhodesians and accommodating Smith in the Admiral's cabin on [[HMS Kent (D12)|HMS ''Kent'']], which was moored alongside.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=536}} Marked progress towards agreement was made\u2014for example, Wilson dropped altogether the transition period under a colonial Governor\u2014but the Rhodesian delegation now demurred on a new British proposal, the \"double safeguard\". This would involve elected black Rhodesians controlling a blocking quarter in the Rhodesian parliament, and thereafter having the right to appeal passed legislation to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in London. Smith's team accepted the principle of the blocking quarter but agreement could not be reached on the technicalities of it;{{sfn|Wood|2008|pp=542\u2013555}} the involvement of the UK Privy Council was rejected by Smith as a \"ridiculous\" provision that would prejudice Rhodesia's sovereignty.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=192}} The ''Fearless'' summit ended with a joint Anglo-Rhodesian statement asserting that \"both sides recognise that a very wide gulf still remains\", but were prepared to continue negotiations in Salisbury. This never occurred.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=192}}\n\n===A republic; failed accord with Douglas\u2013Home===\n{{multiple image\n| direction = vertical\n| image1    = Flag of Rhodesia (1964\u20131968).svg\n| width1    = 140\n| alt1      = A sky blue flag with the Union Jack in the upper-left-hand corner, and a coat of arms on the right.\n| caption1  = Rhodesian [[Blue Ensign|Sky Blue Ensign]], used until 1968{{refn|This overall design dated back to 1923, but a darker blue field was used until 1964, when the shade was lightened to make the Rhodesian flag more recognisable.{{sfn|Smith|1976|p=46}}|group=n|name=\"flags\"}}\n| image2    = Flag of Rhodesia (1968\u20131979).svg\n| width2    = 140\n| alt2      = A flag with vertical green, white and green stripes, with a coat of arms on the central white stripe.\n| caption2  = Rhodesian green-and-white [[Triband (flag)|triband]], adopted in 1968\n}}\n\nWith their hopes of Commonwealth realm status through a settlement with Britain dimming, Smith and the RF began to seriously consider the alternative of a republic as early as December 1966, after the ''Tiger'' talks.{{sfn|Wood|2008|p=254}} Republicanism was presented as a means to clarify Rhodesia's claimed constitutional status, end ambiguity regarding ties with Britain and elicit official foreign recognition and acceptance.{{sfn|Strack|1978|pp=51\u201352}} Smith's government began exploring a republican constitution in March 1967.{{sfn|Rowland|1978|pp=255\u2013256}} The [[Union Jack]] and Rhodesia's Commonwealth-style [[flag of Rhodesia|national flag]]\u2014a [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] [[Blue Ensign|Sky Blue Ensign]] with the Union Jack in the canton\u2014were formally superseded on 11 November 1968, the third anniversary of UDI, by a new national flag: a green-white-green vertical [[Triband (flag)|triband]], [[Charge (heraldry)|charged]] centrally with the [[coat of arms of Rhodesia|Rhodesian coat of arms]].{{sfn|Young|1969|p=585}} After the electorate voted \"yes\" in a June 1969 [[1969 Rhodesian constitutional referendum|referendum]] both to a new constitution and to the abandoning of symbolic ties to the Crown, Smith declared Rhodesia a republic on 2 March 1970. The 1969 constitution introduced a [[President of Rhodesia|President]] as head of state, a multiracial senate, separate black and white electoral rolls (each with qualifications) and a mechanism whereby the number of black MPs would increase in line with the proportion of income tax revenues paid by black citizens. This process would stop once blacks had the same number of seats as whites; the declared goal was not majority rule, but rather \"parity between the races\".{{sfn|Rowland|1978|pp=255\u2013256}}\n\n[[File:Alec Douglas-Home (c1963).jpg|thumb|upright|left|British [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Alec Douglas-Home|Sir Alec Douglas-Home]], with whom Smith signed a short-lived accord in 1971|alt=A photograph of Sir Alec Douglas-Home]]\nNo country recognised the Rhodesian republic.{{sfn|Strack|1978|pp=51\u201352}} The RF was decisively returned to power in the first [[1970 Rhodesian general election|election]] held as a republic, on 10 April 1970, winning all 50 white seats.{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|pp=72\u201373}} Hopes for an Anglo-Rhodesian rapprochement were boosted two months later when the Conservatives won a surprise [[1970 United Kingdom general election|election]] victory in the UK. [[Edward Heath]] took over as Prime Minister while Douglas-Home became [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]]. Talks between Douglas-Home and Smith began with a lengthy meeting in Salisbury in April 1971 and continued until a tentative understanding was reached in early November. A UK delegation headed by Douglas-Home and the Attorney General [[Peter Rawlinson, Baron Rawlinson of Ewell|Sir Peter Rawlinson]] flew to Salisbury on 15 November for negotiations over a new constitution, and after six days of discussion an accord was signed on 21 November 1971.{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=403}}\n\nThe constitution agreed upon was based largely on the one Rhodesia had just adopted, but would eventually bring about a black majority in parliament. Black representation in the House would be immediately increased, and a majority of both black and white MPs would have to approve retrogressive legislation; blacks would thus wield an effective veto \"as long as they voted solidly together\", [[Robert Blake, Baron Blake|Robert Blake]] comments.{{sfn|Blake|1977|pp=403\u2013404}} \"The principle of majority rule was enshrined with safeguards ensuring that there could be no legislation which could impede this,\" Smith wrote in his memoirs. \"On the other hand, there would be no mad rush into [[one man, one vote]] with all the resultant corruption, nepotism, chaos and economic disaster which we had witnessed in all the countries around us.\"{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=152\u2013157}}\n\nThe UK announced a test of opinion in Rhodesia to be undertaken by a four-man commission headed by the veteran judge [[Edward Pearce, Baron Pearce|Lord Pearce]].{{refn|The other members were [[Maurice Henry Dorman|Sir Maurice Dorman]], the former [[Governor-General of Malta]]; [[Glyn Smallwood Jones|Sir Glyn Smallwood Jones]], the last [[Governor-General of Malawi]]; and [[David Ormsby-Gore, 5th Baron Harlech|Lord Harlech]].{{sfn|Blake|1977|p=404}}|group=n|name=\"pearcecom\"}} All four population groups\u2014black, white, [[coloured]] (mixed) and [[Indians in Zimbabwe|Asian]]\u2014would have to approve the terms for Britain to proceed. ZANU and ZAPU supporters quickly formed the [[United African National Council|African National Council]] (later the United African National Council, or UANC) to organise and co-ordinate black opposition to the deal. Bishop [[Abel Muzorewa]], the first black man to have been ordained as such in Rhodesia, was installed as the movement's leader.{{sfn|Cilliers|1984|p=23}} The Pearce Commission finished its work on 12 March 1972 and published its report two months later\u2014it described white, coloured and Asian Rhodesians as in favour of the terms by 98%, 97% and 96% respectively, and black citizens as against them by an unspecified large majority.{{sfn|Brownell|2011|p=184}} This came as a great shock to the white community \"and a deep disappointment to those in Britain who hoped to get rid of this tiresome albatross\", Blake records.{{sfn|Blake|1977|pp=404\u2013405}} Smith condemned the Pearce Commissioners as \"naive and inept\".{{sfn|Godwin|Hancock|1995|p=82}}{{refn|Berlyn, a poet who travelled with the Pearce Commissioners as a journalist for the Salisbury ''Sunday Mail'', was also critical, contending that the commission members did not understand the mindset of black Rhodesians, consulted less than 6% of them and gave explanations the crowds found inadequate or confusing, thereby contributing to the terms' rejection. She also described \"a certain amount of [black nationalist] intimidation\" and alleged bad faith among certain UK officials.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=204\u2013206}}|group=n|name=\"pearce\"}} The UK withdrew from negotiations,{{sfn|Blake|1977|pp=404\u2013405}} but neither government abandoned the accord entirely. \"I would ask them [the black people of Rhodesia] to look again very carefully at what they rejected,\" Douglas-Home told the House of Commons; \"the proposals are still available because Mr Smith has not withdrawn or modified them.\"{{sfn|Loney|1975|p=182}}\n\n===Bush War===\n{{main|Rhodesian Bush War}}\n[[File:Rhodesian African Rifles, Lake Kariba, December 1976.png|thumb|[[Rhodesian Army]] soldiers on [[Lake Kariba]] in 1976, during the [[Rhodesian Bush War|Bush War]]|alt=Two men in military fatigues handle a machine gun on the side of a boat]]\nThe [[Rhodesian Bush War]] (or Second ''[[Chimurenga]]''), which had been underway at a low level since before UDI, began in earnest in December 1972 when ZANLA attacked farms in north-eastern Rhodesia.{{sfn|Binda|2008|pp=133\u2013136}} The [[Rhodesian Security Forces]] mounted a strong counter-campaign over the next two years.{{sfn|Cilliers|1984|p=21}} Muzorewa re-engaged with Smith in August 1973, accepting the 1971\u201372 Douglas-Home terms, and the two signed a statement to that effect on 17 August.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=213\u2013215}} The UANC executive repudiated this in May 1974, but talks between Smith and Muzorewa continued sporadically.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=213\u2013215}} The RF again won a clean sweep of the 50 white seats in the July 1974 [[1974 Rhodesian general election|general election]].{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=13}}\n\nRhodesia's early counter-insurgency successes were undone by political shifts in the guerrillas' favour overseas. The April 1974 [[Carnation Revolution]] in Lisbon led to Mozambique's transformation over the next year from a Portuguese territory friendly to Smith's government into a [[People's Republic of Mozambique|communist state]] openly allied with ZANU.{{sfn|Cilliers|1984|pp=22\u201324}} Wilson and Labour returned to power in the UK in March 1974.{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=17}} Portugal's withdrawal made Rhodesia hugely dependent on South Africa,{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|pp=17, 33}} but Smith still insisted that he held a strong position. \"If it takes one year, five years, ten years, we're prepared to ride it out,\" he told the RF congress on 20 September 1974. \"Our stand is clear and unambiguous. Settlement is desirable, but only on our terms.\"{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=14}}\n\nThe geopolitical situation tilted further against Smith in December 1974 when the South African Prime Minister [[B. J. Vorster|B&nbsp;J Vorster]] pressured him into accepting a [[d\u00e9tente]] initiative involving the [[Frontline States]] of Zambia, Tanzania and Botswana (Mozambique and Angola would join the following year).{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=18}} Vorster had concluded that Rhodesia's position was untenable and that South African interests would be better served by collaborating with black African governments over a Rhodesian settlement; he hoped that success in this might win South Africa some international legitimacy and allow it to retain apartheid.{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=48}} D\u00e9tente forced a ceasefire, giving the guerrillas time to regroup, and required the Rhodesians to release the ZANU and ZAPU leaders so they could attend a conference in Rhodesia, united under the UANC banner and led by Muzorewa.{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|pp=33\u201337}} When Rhodesia stopped releasing black nationalist prisoners on the grounds that ZANLA and ZIPRA were not observing the ceasefire, Vorster harried Smith further by withdrawing the [[South African Police]], which had been helping the Rhodesians patrol the countryside.{{sfn|Cilliers|1984|pp=22\u201324}}{{refn|This followed a much-publicised incident in late December 1974 when a group of ZANLA guerrillas led by Herbert Shungu in north-eastern Rhodesia shot and killed a group of six unarmed policemen, five of them South Africans, having invited them out to discuss terms for the insurgents' surrender.{{sfn|Moorcraft|McLaughlin|2008|p=40}}|group=n|name=\"shungu\"}} Smith remained stubborn, saying in the run-up to the conference that \"We have no policy in Rhodesia to hand over to a black majority government\" and that his government instead favoured \"a qualified franchise for all Rhodesians&nbsp;... [to] ensure that government will be retained in responsible hands for all times\".{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=42}}\n\n[[File:Joshua Nkomo (1978).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Joshua Nkomo]], the leader of [[Zimbabwe African People's Union|ZAPU]], one of the main black nationalist parties in Rhodesia|alt=A black and white photograph of Joshua Nkomo]]\nNkomo remained unchallenged at the head of ZAPU, but the ZANU leadership had become contested between its founding president, the Reverend [[Ndabaningi Sithole]], and [[Robert Mugabe]], a former teacher from [[Mashonaland]] who had recently won an internal election in prison. When they were released in December 1974 under the d\u00e9tente terms, Mugabe went to Mozambique to consolidate his leadership of the guerrillas, while Sithole joined Muzorewa's delegation.{{sfn|Cilliers|1984|pp=22\u201324}} It had been agreed that the talks would take place within Rhodesia, but the black nationalists refused to meet on ground they perceived as not neutral. The Rhodesians insisted on abiding by the accord and negotiating inside the country. To please both camps the conference was held on a train halfway across the [[Victoria Falls Bridge]] on the border between Rhodesia and Zambia; the delegations sat on opposite sides of the frontier. The [[Victoria Falls Conference (1975)|conference]], which took place on 26 August 1975 with Kaunda and Vorster as mediators, failed to produce a settlement; each side accused the other of being unreasonable.{{sfn|BBC|1975}} Smith afterwards held direct talks with Nkomo and ZAPU in Salisbury, but these also led nowhere; Nkomo proposed an immediate transition to an interim government headed by himself, which Smith rejected.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=221}} Guerrilla incursions picked up strongly in the first months of 1976.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=191}}\n\nOn 20 March 1976, Smith gave a televised speech including what became his most quoted utterance. \"I don't believe in majority rule ever in Rhodesia\u2014not in 1,000 years,\" he said. \"I repeat that I believe in blacks and whites working together. If one day it is white and the next day it is black, I believe we have failed and it will be a disaster for Rhodesia.\"{{sfn|Godwin|2007}} The first sentence of this statement became commonly quoted as evidence that Smith was a crude racist who would never compromise with the black nationalists, even though the speech was one in which Smith had said that power-sharing with black Rhodesians was inevitable and that \"we have got to accept that in the future Rhodesia is a country for black and white, not white as opposed to black and vice versa\".{{sfn|Godwin|2007}}{{sfn|Godwin|Hancock|1995|p=152}} The \"not in 1,000 years\" comment was, according to [[Peter Godwin (writer)|Peter Godwin]], an attempt to reassure the RF's right wing, which opposed any transition whatsoever, that white Rhodesians would not be sold out.{{sfn|Godwin|2007}} In her 1978 biography of Smith, Berlyn comments that regardless of whether the statement was \"taken out of context, or whether his actual intent was misinterpreted\", this was one of his greatest blunders as Prime Minister as it gave obvious ammunition to his detractors.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=23}}\n\n[[File:Henry Kissinger.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Henry Kissinger]], the [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]], was instrumental in Smith's public acceptance in 1976 of the principle of majority rule.|alt=A black and white photograph of Henry Kissinger]]\n[[Henry Kissinger]], the [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]], announced a formal interest in the Rhodesian situation in February 1976, and over the next half-year held discussions with the United Kingdom, South Africa and the Frontline States in what became the \"Anglo-American initiative\".{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|p=88}} Meeting Smith in [[Pretoria]] on 18 September 1976, Kissinger proposed majority rule after a transition period of two years. According to Smith, Kissinger told him he considered his participation in the \"demise of Rhodesia\" to be \"one of the great tragedies of my life\".{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=199\u2013201}} He strongly encouraged Smith to accept his deal, though he knew it was unpalatable to him, as any future offer could only be worse from Smith's standpoint\u2014especially if, as expected, US President [[Gerald Ford]] lost the upcoming [[1976 United States presidential election|election]] to [[Jimmy Carter]]. Smith expressed great reluctance, but agreed on 24 September after Vorster intimated that South Africa might cut off financial and military aid if he refused.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=209}} It was the first time Smith had publicly accepted the principles of unconditional majority rule and one man, one vote.{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|p=88}} However, the Frontline States then abruptly revised their stance and turned the Kissinger terms down, saying that any transition period was unacceptable. The UK quickly arranged an all-party conference in [[Geneva]], Switzerland to try to salvage a solution.{{sfn|Wessels|2010|p=162}} ZANU and ZAPU announced that they would attend this and any summit thereafter as a joint \"Patriotic Front\" (PF), including members of both parties under a combined leadership. The [[Geneva Conference (1976)|Geneva Conference]], held between October and December 1976 under British mediation, also failed.{{sfn|Wessels|2010|pp=162\u2013164}}\n\n===Internal Settlement and Lancaster House; becoming Zimbabwe===\n\nSmith's moves towards a settlement with black nationalist groups prompted outrage in sections of Rhodesian Front's right wing, but he remained unassailable within the party as a whole, which had in late 1975 granted him a mandate to negotiate for the best possible settlement however he saw fit.{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=87}} The split in the party ultimately led to the defection in July 1977 of 12&nbsp;RF MPs after Smith introduced legislation to remove racial criteria from the Land Tenure Act.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=231}}{{refn|The Land Apportionment Act had been slightly reformed and thus renamed in 1969.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=231}}|group=n|name=\"tenure\"}}\n\nThe loss of these seats to the breakaway [[Rhodesian Action Party]], which opposed any conciliation with black nationalists, meant that Smith now only barely had the two-thirds majority in parliament he would need to change the constitution, as he would have to in the event of a settlement. He therefore called an early [[1977 Rhodesian general election|election]], and on 31 August 1977 roundly defeated the defectors\u2014\"the dirty dozen\", the RF called them\u2014as well as all other opposition; for the third time in seven years, the RF had won all 50 white seats. The party revolt turned out to be a blessing in disguise for Smith, Berlyn comments, as it allowed him to \"shed the dead wood of the right wing\", giving him more freedom in negotiations with the nationalists.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=231}} The need for a settlement was becoming urgent\u2014the war was escalating sharply, white emigration was climbing and the economy was starting to struggle as the UN sanctions finally began to have a serious effect.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=231}}\n\n[[File:Muzorewa 1978 d.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Bishop [[Abel Muzorewa]], the country's first black Prime Minister, who succeeded Smith in June 1979 following the [[Internal Settlement]]|alt=A portrait photograph of Abel Muzorewa]]\nIn March 1978, Smith and non-militant nationalist groups headed by Muzorewa, Sithole and Chief [[Jeremiah Chirau]] agreed what became the \"[[Internal Settlement]]\", under which the country would be reconstituted as [[Zimbabwe Rhodesia]] in June 1979 after [[1979 Zimbabwe Rhodesia general election|multiracial elections]]. ZANU and ZAPU were invited to participate, but refused; Nkomo sardonically dubbed Smith's black colleagues \"the blacksmiths\".{{sfn|Binda|2007|p=327}} The deal was badly received abroad, partly because it kept the police, the military, the judiciary and the civil service in white hands.{{sfn|Chikuhwa|2004|pp=30\u201332}} There would be a senate of 20 blacks and 10 whites, and whites would be reserved 28 out of 100 seats in the new House of Assembly.{{refn|Whites would elect 20 of these on a separate electoral roll; these 20 MPs would then nominate a list of 16 candidates from whom eight would be elected by all registered voters.{{sfn|Chikuhwa|2004|pp=30\u201332}}|group=n|name=\"zimrhoseats\"}} Smith and Nkomo re-entered negotiations in August 1978, but these ended after ZIPRA shot down an [[Air Rhodesia]] passenger flight on 3 September and [[Air Rhodesia Flight 825|massacred survivors]] at the crash site.{{sfn|Moorcraft|McLaughlin|2008|pp=153\u2013154}} Smith cut off talks, introduced [[martial law]] across most of the country and ordered reprisal attacks on guerrilla positions.{{sfn|Moorcraft|McLaughlin|2008|p=154}} Smith, Muzorewa and Sithole toured the US in October 1978 to promote their settlement,{{sfn|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|p=320}} and met Kissinger, Ford and others including the future President [[Ronald Reagan]].{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=270\u2013277}} On 11 December, ZANLA attacked Salisbury's oil storage depot, causing a fire that lasted six days and destroyed a quarter of Rhodesia's fuel.{{sfn|Cilliers|1984|p=49}} Two months later ZIPRA [[Air Rhodesia Flight 827|downed]] another civilian flight, this time killing all on board.{{sfn|Moorcraft|McLaughlin|2008|p=157}}\n\nAfter whites endorsed the Internal Settlement by 85% in a [[1979 Rhodesian constitutional referendum|referendum]] on 30 January 1979,{{sfn|Daume|1980|p=737}} Smith dissolved the Rhodesian parliament for the last time on 28 February.{{sfn|Chikuhwa|2004|p=32}} The RF won all the white seats in the April 1979 elections while Muzorewa and the UANC won a majority in the common roll seats with 67% of the popular vote;{{sfn|Winn|1979}} the PF rejected this, however, as did the UN, which passed a [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 448|resolution]] branding it a \"sham\".{{sfn|UN Security Council|1979}} Sithole, astounded that his party had won only 12 seats to the UANC's 51, suddenly turned against the settlement and alleged that the polls had been stage-managed in Muzorewa's favour.<ref>{{Harvnb|Cilliers|1984|p=53}}; {{Harvnb|Mungazi|2000|p=162}}.</ref> Mugabe dismissed the bishop as a \"neocolonial puppet\" and pledged to continue ZANLA's campaign \"to the last man\";{{sfn|Winn|1979}} Nkomo similarly committed ZIPRA.{{sfn|Mungazi|2000|p=162}} On 1 June 1979, the day of the country's official reconstitution as Zimbabwe Rhodesia, Muzorewa replaced Smith as Prime Minister, at the head of a [[Government of Zimbabwe Rhodesia|UANC\u2013RF coalition Cabinet]] made up of 12 blacks and five whites.{{sfn|Williams|Hackland|1988|p=289}} Smith was included as [[Minister without portfolio]]; Nkomo promptly dubbed him the \"Minister with all the portfolios\".{{sfn|Moorcraft|1990}}\n\nAn observer group from the UK Conservative Party did regard the April 1979 elections as fair,{{sfn|Moorcraft|1990}} and [[Margaret Thatcher]], the Conservative leader, was personally disposed to recognise Muzorewa's government and lift sanctions. The potential significance of the Conservative victory in the May 1979 British [[1979 United Kingdom general election|general election]] was not lost on Smith, who wrote to Thatcher: \"All Rhodesians thank God for your magnificent victory.\"{{sfn|Moore|2013|p=449}} The [[United States Senate|US Senate]] passed a resolution urging President Carter to remove sanctions and declare Zimbabwe Rhodesia legitimate,{{sfn|Mungazi|2000|pp=163\u2013166}} but Carter and his Cabinet remained strongly opposed.{{sfn|Moore|2013|p=449}} Carter and Thatcher ultimately decided against accepting Zimbabwe Rhodesia, noting the continued international support for the guerrillas.<ref name=notrecognise>{{Harvnb|Gowlland-Debbas|1990|p=82}}; {{Harvnb|Mungazi|2000|pp=163\u2013166}}; {{Harvnb|Tamarkin|1990|pp=246\u2013249}}.</ref> After the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 1979|Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]] in [[Lusaka]] in August 1979, the UK Foreign Secretary [[Peter Carington, 6th Baron Carrington|Lord Carrington]] invited the Zimbabwe Rhodesian government and the Patriotic Front to attend an all-party constitutional conference at [[Lancaster House]] in London, starting on 10 September.{{sfn|Mungazi|2000|p=169}}\n\nSmith was part of Muzorewa's delegation at Lancaster House. Several aspects of the Internal Settlement constitution, such as a declaration of human rights and a guarantee that land redistributed by the government would be paid for, were retained; it was also agreed to have 20 reserved white seats out of 100 for at least seven years. Fresh elections would be held during a brief period under a British Governor invested with full executive and legislative powers. The new constitution was agreed on 18 October, and on 12 December 1979 the House of Assembly voted to dissolve itself, ending UDI. [[Christopher Soames, Baron Soames|Lord Soames]] arrived in Salisbury later the same day to become Southern Rhodesia's last Governor; among other things he announced that Smith would be granted amnesty for declaring independence.{{sfn|Mungazi|2000|p=169}} The final [[Lancaster House Agreement]] was signed on 21 December.{{sfn|Chikuhwa|2004|pp=32\u201333}} Smith was the only member of any delegation to openly oppose the accords; he refused to attend the signing ceremony and boycotted the post-agreement party, instead having dinner with former RAF comrades and [[Group Captain]] [[Sir Douglas Bader]].{{sfn|The Times|2007}}\n\nThe UK government and the international community ultimately declared the February 1980 [[1980 Southern Rhodesian general election|general election]] free and fair,{{sfn|Mungazi|2000|p=171}} though many observers attested to widespread political violence and intimidation of voters, particularly by ZANU (which added Patriotic Front to its name to become \"ZANU\u2013PF\").{{sfn|Kriger|2003|pp=29, 48}} British monitors in the ZANU\u2013PF-dominated eastern provinces were strongly critical, reporting \"brutal 'disciplinary murders' as examples of the fate awaiting those who failed to conform\", name-taking and \"claims to the possession of machines which would reveal how individuals had voted\".{{sfn|Kriger|2003|pp=47\u201348}} The [[Commonwealth Observer Groups|Commonwealth Observer Group]] acknowledged that irregularities were occurring but ruled that accounts were exaggerated.{{sfn|Kriger|2003|pp=47\u201348}} After the RF won all 20 white seats, Soames announced late on 4 March 1980 that Mugabe and ZANU\u2013PF had won 57 of the 80 common roll seats, giving them a majority in the new House of Assembly.{{sfn|Kriger|2003|p=52}}\n\nMugabe invited Smith to his house that evening and according to Smith treated him \"most courteously\"; Mugabe expressed joy at inheriting a \"wonderful country\" with modern infrastructure and a viable economy, outlined plans for gradual reform that Smith found reasonable, and said that he hoped to stay in regular contact. This meeting had a profound effect on the former Prime Minister.{{sfn|Smith|1997|pp=341\u2013342}} Having denounced Mugabe as an \"apostle of Satan\" before the election, Smith now publicly endorsed him as \"sober and responsible\".{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=14}} \"If this were a true picture, then there could be hope instead of despair,\" he recalled in his autobiography. \"When I got home I said to Janet that I hoped it was not an hallucination.\"{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=342}}\n\n==Opposition==\n===First years under Mugabe===\n[[File:Persconferentie Robert Magabe , president Zimbabwe, op Schiphol na driedaags bez, Bestanddeelnr 932-1958.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Robert Mugabe]], elected [[Prime Minister of Zimbabwe|Prime Minister]] in 1980, faced an official opposition headed by Smith until 1987.|alt=Robert Mugabe, surrounded by microphones]]\nThe new [[Parliament of Zimbabwe|Zimbabwean parliament]] opened on 15 May 1980, a month after formal independence from Britain, with Smith as the reconstituted country's first Leader of the Opposition. Continuing a long-standing tradition from the Rhodesian era, the government and opposition entered the House in pairs\u2014Mugabe and Smith walked in side by side with their respective MPs following, \"aptly symbolis[ing] the mood of reconciliation\", [[Martin Meredith]] comments.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=44}} With around 1,000 whites leaving Zimbabwe each month, Smith took to the radio to urge them to stay and give Mugabe's new order a chance,{{sfn|Kalley|Schoeman|Andor|1999|p=712}} but over half of the country's whites left within three years. As Meredith records, the 100,000 or so who remained \"retreated into their own world of clubs, sporting activities, and comfortable living\".{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=55}} Mugabe made great efforts when he first took power to endear himself to the white farming community, which accounted for at least 75% of Zimbabwe's agricultural output.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=111}} Amid booming Zimbabwean commodity prices in the years immediately following 1980, many white commercial farmers came to support Mugabe.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=45}} The new Prime Minister continued cordially meeting Smith until the RF leader took him to task in 1981 for openly calling for a [[one-party state]]; Smith said this was putting off foreign investors.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=55}} Mugabe was not impressed and, according to Smith, refused to ever meet him again.{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=372}}\n\nAs Mugabe's main opponent in Parliament at the head of the [[Republican Front (Zimbabwe)|Republican Front]] (as the RF renamed itself in 1981), Smith presented himself as the guardian of what he called Zimbabwe's \"white tribe\". He spoke gloomily about Zimbabwe's future prospects, repeatedly accused the Mugabe administration of corruption, malevolence and general incompetence,{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=55}} and criticised Mugabe's support for a one-party system.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=50}} The RF took an increasingly confrontational line in the House after Mugabe and other government ministers began regularly pouring scorn on the white community in national broadcasts and other media.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=50}} Amid rising tensions with South Africa, various white Zimbabweans were arrested, accused of being South African agents, and tortured. When Smith complained about whites being imprisoned without trial under emergency powers, a number of ZANU\u2013PF MPs pointed out that they themselves had been detained under that same legislation, and for far longer, by Smith's government. Mugabe openly admitted torturing suspected spies, had some who were found not guilty by the High Court immediately rearrested on the street outside, and accused Western critics of caring only because the people in question were white.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|pp=53\u201354}}\n\nSmith visited Britain and the United States in November 1982, and spoke scathingly about Zimbabwe to reporters, claiming that Mugabe was turning the country into a totalitarian Marxist\u2013Leninist dictatorship. Government retribution was immediate. On Smith's return home, police raided an art exhibition hosting him as guest of honour in Harare (as Salisbury had been [[place names in Zimbabwe|renamed]] in April 1982) and took all the attendees in for questioning, ostensibly because of suspicions it might be an illegal political meeting. A week later, police seized his passport, according to a government statement because his criticism of Zimbabwe while abroad constituted \"political bad manners and hooliganism\".{{sfn|Meredith|2007|pp=55\u201356}} Police meticulously searched his Harare house and Gwenoro over the next week, confiscating firearms, personal papers and a diary. Smith told reporters all this was \"part of the game to intimidate me and so demoralise the whites\".{{sfn|Meredith|2007|pp=55\u201356}} Some RF MPs left the party to sit with ZANU\u2013PF or as independents, feeling that constantly confronting Mugabe was ill-advised and unnecessary. Smith remained convinced that nobody would stand up for white Zimbabweans if they did not stick together and defend their interests in parliament.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|pp=55\u201356}}\n\n[[Smith Hempstone]] later wrote that the former Prime Minister had resolved to \"go down&nbsp;... with all rhetorical guns blazing\".{{sfn|Hempstone|1986}} This was in spite of increasingly unstable health; in June 1982 he collapsed in the House of Assembly, clutching at his side and shaking.{{sfn|Glasgow Herald|1982}} Half a year later he had to arrange treatment in South Africa for a condition stemming from [[Atherosclerosis|hardening of the arteries]]. The government's confiscation of his passport and two refusals of its return prevented him from going, so in April 1983 Smith successfully applied for a [[British passport]]. \"I'll still try to get my Zimbabwean passport back,\" he said. \"I was born here and that is the passport I should travel on.\"{{sfn|Glasgow Herald|1983}} Smith regained his Zimbabwean papers after about a year.{{sfn|Schuettler|2000}} In 1984 he declared his intention to renounce his British nationality to abide by a new Zimbabwean law outlawing [[multiple citizenship]]. Britain did not recognise this legislation; according to Smith, British officials refused to take his UK passport when he tried to return it.{{sfn|Schuettler|2000}}\n\n===''Gukurahundi''; last years in politics===\nAfter the already tense relations between ZANU\u2013PF and ZAPU disintegrated amid Mugabe's wish to adopt a one-party system in Zimbabwe, Mugabe expelled Nkomo from the government in February 1982, accusing him and ZAPU of plotting a coup. About a year later, Mugabe deployed the North Korean-trained [[5th Brigade (Zimbabwe)|5th Brigade]] to [[Matabeleland]], ZAPU's heartland, where it massacred thousands of civilians accused of supporting \"dissidents\" in what came to be called ''[[Gukurahundi]]''.<ref name=meredithhill/> Meredith asserts that this far exceeded anything that had occurred during the Bush War, an opinion shared by Geoff Hill.<ref name=meredithhill>{{Harvnb|Meredith|2007|pp=62\u201373}}; {{Harvnb|Hill|2005|p=77}}.</ref> Some white farmers were also killed.{{sfn|Faul|1985}} Estimates for the number of deaths during the five-year ''Gukurahundi'' campaign range from 10,000 to 30,000.{{sfn|Hill|2005|p=77}} Mugabe concurrently took steps to marginalise the other main black nationalist leaders from the ''Chimurenga''. Nkomo fled to the UK in March 1983, fearing for his life;{{sfn|Hill|2005|p=77}} Sithole similarly exiled himself in the United States.{{sfn|Daily Telegraph|2000}} Muzorewa stayed in Zimbabwe and was detained in late 1983 for alleged \"subversive links\" with South Africa.{{sfn|Chikuhwa|2004|p=37}} On arriving in England, Nkomo accused Mugabe of genocide and asserted that \"Things are worse now than they ever were under Ian Smith\".{{sfn|Hill|2005|p=77}} Mugabe denied that anything improper was happening and put reports to the contrary down to \"reactionary foreign journalists\".{{sfn|Hill|2005|p=84}}\n\nThe Zimbabwean government publicly threatened Smith on a regular basis, but in practice left him and his property largely untouched\u2014Mugabe frequently pointed to Smith's freedom as evidence of Zimbabwe's reconciliation policy.{{sfn|Los Angeles Times|2002}} Smith renamed the RF the [[Conservative Alliance of Zimbabwe]] (CAZ) on 21 July 1984, concurrently removing racial criteria for membership and inviting black Zimbabweans to join.{{sfn|New York Times|1984}} The CAZ was very successful in the 1985 [[1985 Zimbabwean parliamentary election|parliamentary election]], winning 15 of the 20 white seats; Smith won decisively in Bulawayo Central. Mugabe interpreted this as \"the racists of this country\" defying his government and rejecting reconciliation,<ref>{{Harvnb|Fisher|2010|pp=43\u201344}}; {{Harvnb|Meredith|2007|pp=55\u201356}}.</ref> and immediately pledged to abolish the white seats, which he said compromised \"the sovereignty of our people\".{{sfn|Sakaike|1985}} After Smith described Mugabe's government as \"illiterate\" on [[BBC television]] in November 1985, Mugabe told the House of Assembly Smith was \"an incorrigible racist\" who \"should long ago have been hanged and hanged publicly\".{{sfn|Associated Press|1985}} Later that month, Smith's close friend and long-standing political associate \"Boss\" Lilford, who had provided much of the finance to form the RF, was found beaten and shot to death on his ranch.{{refn|Gunmen reportedly tied the 77-year-old Lilford's hands behind his back with an electric cord and beat him before shooting him in the head. One of Lilford's friends told press that the attackers left his house entirely in order; the only thing missing was a small car that police found abandoned the next day in [[Chitungwiza]].{{sfn|Faul|1985}}|group=n|name=\"lilforddeath\"}} Smith described Lilford afterwards as a man \"who was prepared to die for [his] principles\", but refused to openly discuss any possible political motive, saying simply that \"it would be premature to come to conclusions\".{{sfn|Faul|1985}}\n\nSmith was by now in the twilight of his career, but his outspoken, confrontational stance continued to irritate the ZANU\u2013PF government. He was declared a \"fifth columnist\" by the Information Minister [[Nathan Shamuyarira]] in February 1987 after he advised a group of South African businessmen that they could survive economic sanctions if white South Africans stood together.{{sfn|Glasgow Herald|1987}} Three months later, after he was suspended from the Zimbabwean parliament for a year over his comments in South Africa and criticism of ZANU\u2013PF, he resigned as leader of the CAZ.{{sfn|Chikuhwa|2004|p=38}} His four decades as an MP formally ended in September 1987 when, as allowed under the Lancaster House terms, ZANU\u2013PF scrapped the white seats amid sweeping constitutional reforms. The office of Prime Minister was abolished in October; Mugabe became the country's first [[executive president|executive]] [[President of Zimbabwe|President]] two months later.{{sfn|Chikuhwa|2004|pp=38\u201339}} Mugabe and Nkomo signed a unity accord at the same time merging ZAPU into ZANU\u2013PF with the stated goal of a Marxist\u2013Leninist one-party state.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=73}}\n\nThis marked the end of Smith's front-line political career\u2014[[Gerald Smith (Zimbabwean politician)|Gerald Smith]] (no relation) replaced him as leader of the CAZ\u2014but he remained active in opposition at a reduced level. In July 1992 he chaired a meeting where the CAZ, Muzorewa's UANC, Sithole's [[Zimbabwe African National Union \u2013 Ndonga|ZANU\u2013Ndonga]] party and [[Edgar Tekere]]'s [[Zimbabwe Unity Movement]] formed a coalition to challenge Mugabe and ZANU\u2013PF in the next parliamentary election. The result was the short-lived United Front, which Smith agreed to chair, saying he had no more political ambitions and could therefore be regarded as a neutral figurehead.{{sfn|Southscan|1992|p=220}} The United Front quickly failed, largely due to the lack of common ground between the constituent parties, and never contested an election.{{sfn|Nkiwane|1998|pp=108\u2013109}} Another brief collaboration between Smith, Muzorewa and Sithole in March 2000 also led to nothing.{{sfn|The Times|2007}}\n\n==Retirement==\n[[File:IanSmith1990crop.png|thumb|upright|Smith in 1990, speaking at a dinner held in his honour by the [[Conservative Monday Club]] in England|alt=An elderly-looking Ian Smith]]\n\nThe elderly Ian Smith lived in an unassuming house in Harare where, according to [[David Blair (journalist)|David Blair]], \"the front gate always stood open and virtually anyone who walked up the drive would be invited in for tea\".{{sfn|Blair|2007}} He still owned Gwenoro, but employed a manager to run it after Janet's death in 1994.{{sfn|Thornycroft|2012}} He insisted that he would never leave Zimbabwe.{{sfn|Fisher|2010|p=90}} \"Don't get fazed by the riots, hold your head high, do not be afraid,\" a friend reported him saying. \"Show you are not budging and the government will leave you alone.\"{{sfn|Fisher|2010|p=90}} He dedicated much of his 1997 autobiography, ''[[The Great Betrayal: The Memoirs of Ian Douglas Smith|The Great Betrayal]]'',{{refn|Re-released as ''Bitter Harvest: The Great Betrayal'' in 2001{{sfn|Smith|2001|p=i}}|group=n|name=\"bitterharvest\"}} to criticising the Mugabe administration and a long succession of British figures he considered to have let him and Rhodesia down; he also defended and attempted to justify his actions as Prime Minister,{{sfn|Schwarz|2011|pp=414\u2013415, 423}} and praised [[Nelson Mandela]], calling him Africa's \"first black statesman\".{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=412}} Smith's enduring popularity among white Zimbabweans was evidenced by the long queues they formed to have him sign copies of the book on its release in Harare in December 1997. \"They were captured, hiding their faces and turning to the wall, as television cameras recorded their 'betrayal' for the evening news,\" Josephine Fisher records.{{sfn|Fisher|2010|p=90}} Not all of the country's whites admired Smith; some felt that his obstinate refusal to acknowledge what they saw as past errors caused the whole white community to be resented and viewed with suspicion.{{sfn|Fisher|2010|p=90}}\n\n===2000\u20132002: back in the public eye===\nAccording to Meredith, governmental mismanagement and widespread corruption within the ZANU\u2013PF order led to Mugabe and others enriching themselves considerably at the expense of the country as a whole.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=17}} In Meredith's view, the average Zimbabwean was worse off in 2000 than he had been in 1980: \"average wages were lower, unemployment had trebled, public services were crumbling, and life expectancy was falling\".{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=17}} Opposition to ZANU\u2013PF grew, particularly in the towns and cities.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=17}} In 2000, hoping to win support from rural blacks, Mugabe introduced a fast-track land reform programme under which groups of ZANU\u2013PF activists, officially referred to as \"war veterans\", were sent to take over white-owned farms so the land could be split up, without compensation, and redistributed to black peasant farmers.{{sfn|Meredith|2007|p=17}} White farmers and their black employees were violently forced out, food production plummeted, and the economy collapsed to half the size it had been in 1980.{{sfn|Smith|2013}}\n\nWhen a group of about 50 ZANU\u2013PF activists briefly invaded Gwenoro in May 2000, Smith played down the incident, saying the intruders were just bored and out of work. \"There's no politics on the farm,\" he said.{{sfn|Meldrum|2000}} Five months later, in England to address the [[Oxford Union]], Smith described Mugabe as \"mentally deranged\".{{sfn|Majendie|2000}} The President announced in response that Smith would be arrested and tried for genocide if he ever came back to Zimbabwe, a threat that Smith mocked. \"I would love that. Let him try it,\" he said\u2014\"It would give me the chance to tell the world the truth about this gangster&nbsp;... I will give him the date and time of arrival of my plane so he can meet me at the airport.\"{{sfn|Majendie|2000}} A mass of reporters descended on [[Harare International Airport]] on 7 November 2000 to witness Smith's arrest, but far from being detained, the former Prime Minister was greeted cheerily by immigration officers and allowed through without any obstruction. Telling the waiting pressmen that he was disappointed not to have met any confrontation, he commented: \"We have a president here who is mentally unstable and makes statements that have no bearing on reality\", and went home unmolested.{{sfn|Blair|2000}}\n\nIn early September 2001, ZANU\u2013PF militants again attempted to force Smith off his farm. The former Prime Minister telephoned the provincial Governor, who promptly sent police to remove the invaders. According to Smith, the trespassers were shocked to hear the authorities were taking his side, and left before the police even arrived.{{sfn|Meldrum|MacAskill|2001}} Half a year later, Smith lost his Zimbabwean passport as a result of further tightening of the law regarding multiple citizenship. New legislation passed in 2001 required Zimbabwean citizens to disavow any claim to other nationalities, even if they did not hold foreign passports.{{sfn|Los Angeles Times|2002}} Insisting that Mugabe's government had no right to strip him of Zimbabwean citizenship, Smith refused to renounce his right to British nationality, though he had not held a UK passport for years. Zimbabwean authorities duly refused to renew Smith's passport in March 2002.{{sfn|Blair|2002}} State press reported that he had \"automatically ceased to be a citizen of Zimbabwe\" on the passport's expiry, having failed to renounce British citizenship before a deadline on 8 January that year.{{sfn|Herald|2002}} Smith claimed that his Zimbabwean citizenship had been illegally revoked and that he was now [[statelessness|stateless]], an assertion disputed by the Minister of Home Affairs [[John Nkomo]], who said that Smith could stay in the country, but would not receive a new Zimbabwean passport until he renounced his right to British nationality.{{sfn|Los Angeles Times|2002}}\n\nBy 2002, the white community in Zimbabwe had shrunk to no more than 50,000 people, of whom many, like Smith, were elderly.{{sfn|Blair|2002}} Smith had by this time lost most of his former international prominence\u2014his visit to the UK in 2004 to meet Conservative politicians was largely ignored by the British press{{sfn|Cowell|2007 b}}\u2014but he achieved new domestic popularity and eminence among Zimbabwean opposition supporters, who came to see him as an unbreakable, defiant symbol of resistance to the Mugabe government.<ref>{{Harvnb|Johnson|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Ndlovu|2008}}; {{Harvnb|The Times|2007}}.</ref> According to [[R. W. Johnson|R&nbsp;W Johnson]], a speech he gave to students at the [[University of Zimbabwe]] condemning Mugabe and ZANU\u2013PF as incompetent and corrupt \"gangsters\" earned him a standing ovation.{{sfn|Johnson|2007}} In 2002, Smith challenged Mugabe to come with him to a township to see who got the best welcome. \"Only one of us will come out alive,\" Smith said; \"I'm ready to put that to the test right now. He's not.\"{{sfn|Johnson|2007}}\n\n===Final years and death===\n[[File:St. James Near Muizenberg.jpg|thumb|[[St James, Cape Town|St James]], the [[Cape Town]] suburb where Smith spent his last years|alt=A seaside scene, with a bay and a high mountain in the background]]\nSmith travelled to South Africa for medical treatment in 2005,{{sfn|The Week|2007}} and moved into a retirement home overlooking the sea in [[St James, Cape Town|St James]], a southern suburb of Cape Town.{{sfn|Blair|Thornycroft|2007}} He was reportedly devastated by the death of his son Alec from a heart attack at [[London Heathrow Airport]] in January 2006.{{sfn|Bevan|2007}} Despite some marked differences\u2014Alec had used illegal drugs in his youth,{{sfn|Independent|2006}} and openly opposed his father's policies while he was Prime Minister\u2014they had been very close. The elder Smith had referred to his son as \"my rock\".{{sfn|Independent|2006}} Smith's stepdaughter Jean, who had married the prominent Rhodesian singer-songwriter [[Clem Tholet]] in 1967,{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=28}} was by this time also widowed. She and Robert Smith cared for their stepfather in his final years.{{sfn|Blair|Thornycroft|2007}}\n\nAfter some weeks of illness, Ian Smith died in Cape Town on 20 November 2007 at the age of 88,{{sfn|Blair|Thornycroft|2007}} having suffered a stroke.{{sfn|Cowell|2007 b}} Jean was with him.{{sfn|Blair|Thornycroft|2007}} His ashes were returned to Zimbabwe and scattered by his family at Gwenoro. The farm continued to operate under the ownership of Smith's stepchildren until December 2012, when it was expropriated by the Mugabe regime as part of the land reform programme and given to a technical college.{{sfn|Thornycroft|2012}}\n\nInvestigations into alleged [[electoral fraud]] during the 2008 [[2008 Zimbabwean presidential election|presidential]] and [[2008 Zimbabwean parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] in Zimbabwe, when ZANU\u2013PF was accused of using dead \"ghost voters\" to counter [[Morgan Tsvangirai]] and the [[Movement for Democratic Change \u2013 Tsvangirai|Movement for Democratic Change]] (MDC), revealed that Smith and hundreds of thousands of other dead people were still on the electoral roll.{{sfn|Fields|2013}} According to the Zimbabwe Election Support Network's audit report, published in 2011, deceased \"voters\" made up 27% of the registered electorate.{{sfn|Smith|2011}} Mugabe had insisted during his ultimately victorious campaign in 2008 that he would not allow the MDC to take power even if it won, asserting that \"only God\" could remove him from office.{{sfn|Daily Telegraph|2008}} Smith was finally struck off the voters' roll in April 2013, along with 345,000 other dead people.{{sfn|Fields|2013}} Mugabe resigned the presidency four years later, after ZANU\u2013PF moved to [[impeachment|impeach]] him amid [[2017 Zimbabwean coup d'\u00e9tat|a military coup]].{{sfn|BBC|2017}}\n\n==Character, reputation and legacy==\n[[File:Ian Smith 1975.jpg|thumb|upright|Smith in 1975, as Prime Minister, wearing his [[Royal Air Force]] tie from the Second World War|alt=A photograph of Ian Smith. He is wearing a blue tie with white and red stripes.]]\n\"Smith was a simple man,\" [[Graham Boynton]] wrote soon after his death, \"and it was his rather humourless, one-dimensional Rhodesian-ness that at once made him a hero among his own people and a figure of derision among his enemies\".{{sfn|Boynton|2007}} As leader of the Rhodesian Front and its successors, he was the foremost figure of his country's white community\u2014a \"symbol and father figure\",{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=5}} in Mordechai Tamarkin's phrase, who as Prime Minister \"personified white Rhodesia\".{{sfn|Tamarkin|1990|p=87}} Supporters hailed him as \"a political visionary&nbsp;... who understood the uncomfortable truths of Africa\";{{sfn|BBC|2007}} detractors denounced him as \"an unrepentant racist\".{{sfn|BBC|2007}}\n\nHis determination to preserve the white minority's position in Rhodesia caused many black Africans and others to perceive him as a symbol of iniquitous white rule and racism.<ref>{{Harvnb|Boynton|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Cowell|2007 b}}.</ref> Smith always denied being driven by racial prejudice\u2014in a 1987 interview he asserted that he had been defending Western principles and that \"it was Marxism I fought, not blacks\".{{sfn|Star-Banner|1987}} Above all, he never expressed regret regarding his actions as Prime Minister; he insisted to the end that the political and economic ruination of Zimbabwe under ZANU\u2013PF had borne out his predictions and proven him right.<ref>{{Harvnb|BBC|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Boynton|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Cowell|2007 b}}.</ref>\n\n\"The key to understanding Smith,\" Johnson wrote, \"was that, like other white Rhodesians, he clung to an almost Victorian view of the world both in moral values and in the easy assumptions of British primacy that characterised the empire.\"{{sfn|Johnson|2007}} [[Bill Schwarz]] took a similar line, writing that Smith and his supporters reacted to the British Empire's demise by imagining white Rhodesians to be \"the final survivors of a lost civilisation\",{{sfn|Schwarz|2011|p=438}} charged with \"tak[ing] on the mantle of historic Britain\" in the imperial power's absence.{{sfn|Schwarz|2011|p=399}} \"He spoke endlessly about how Rhodesians had been more British than the British,\" Boynton reflected, \"and how this small community of decent, fair-minded whites had been betrayed by, well, just about everybody he could think of&nbsp;... It was easy to mock Ian Smith, but he was right\u2014both about the betrayals and about the quality of most African politicians\".{{sfn|Boynton|2007}} Smith's \"not in 1,000 years\" quote dominated his obituaries, a development that Peter Godwin, despite his critical stance regarding Smith and his policies, considered \"unfair and inaccurate\": \"Over the years it has become shorn of all context and compressed into a free-floating clip that has now become his epitaph&nbsp;... But there is more than enough for which to quite legitimately criticise Smith, without resorting to fabrication.\"{{sfn|Godwin|2007}}\n\nMemories of his travails on the UK's behalf during the Second World War\u2014\"undoubtedly the central experience of his life\", according to Johnson{{sfn|Johnson|2007}}\u2014were fundamental to the sense of profound betrayal Smith felt when the UK government proved one of his main adversaries as Prime Minister.{{sfn|Daily Telegraph|2007}} The wartime plastic surgery that corrected the wounds to his face left its right side paralysed, giving him a crooked smile and a somewhat blank expression, while his bodily injuries gave him a stoop and a slight limp;{{sfn|Younghusband|1978}} he also could not sit for long periods without pain.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|pp=174\u2013176}} The post-colonial UK Smith encountered as Prime Minister seemed to him \"foreign and somewhat effete\", to quote Kenneth Young, while Smith was \"a foreigner in all but language to most British politicians\u2014a man of convictions so outdated, of tastes so naive, as to make mutual understanding almost impossible.\"{{sfn|Young|1969|p=128}} Smith held most of the British politicians he dealt with in extremely low esteem, considering them to have pushed him and his country into an impossible position where, he asserted in 1970, the decision to take unilateral action was \"forced upon us\".{{sfn|BBC|1970}}\n\nIn his prime, Smith was widely recognised by both contemporaries and rivals as a formidable negotiator.<ref>{{Harvnb|Berlyn|1978|p=239}}; {{Harvnb|Younghusband|1978}}.</ref> Hempstone considered him \"a man too principled (or short-sighted) to compromise with what he regards as wrong\",{{sfn|Hempstone|1986}} while Welensky compared dealing with him to \"trying to nail jelly to a wall\".{{sfn|Daily Telegraph|2007}} He had an \"iron nerve\", to quote his RF colleague [[P. K. van der Byl|P&nbsp;K van der Byl]],{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=24}} and a reputation for \"icy calm\";{{sfn|Younghusband|1978}} he almost never got angry or raised his voice.{{sfn|Younghusband|1978}} He spoke with \"a nasal monologue\" as Peter Younghusband described it\u2014\"uninspiring even by Rhodesian oratorical standards\".{{sfn|Younghusband|1978}} His open, informal association with the general public fostered the impression among white Rhodesians that their Prime Minister was still an \"ordinary, decent fellow\", which Berlyn cites as a major factor in his enduring popularity.{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=23}} Welensky described him in 1978 as wielding an \"almost hypnotic influence\" over the Rhodesian electorate, which helped him to win \"election after election&nbsp;... hands down\".{{sfn|Berlyn|1978|p=112}} He also had the grudging respect of at least some of his black nationalist opponents during the Bush War; one, quoted anonymously by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine in 1976, asserted that \"If we had a leader like Mr Smith, we would have won long ago.\"{{sfn|Minetree|1976}} Sithole, the long-time ZANU leader, said: \"Smith is a fighter. He put up a great fight for his people. We were like two bulls in there, the way we fought. He is a man. I respect him.\"{{sfn|Younghusband|1978}}\n\n[[Patrick Kombayi]], an MDC politician and member of the [[Senate of Zimbabwe|Zimbabwean Senate]], said after Smith's death that Zimbabweans had much to thank him for. \"The roads that we are using today were all built by Smith,\" he said. \"All the infrastructure is Smith's. We never suffered the way we are suffering now because Smith took care of the economy that supported all people and they had enough to eat. When he left power the [British] [[pound sterling|pound]] was on a par with the [[Zimbabwean dollar]], but President Mugabe has killed all that.\"{{sfn|Bevan|2007}} [[David Coltart]], another MDC politician, issued a statement after Smith's death praising him as a man of modesty and integrity, but criticising what Coltart felt to be \"disastrous political decisions as Prime Minister\"; Coltart considered Smith's policies to have radicalised black nationalists, fomented Mugabe's rise to power and thereby \"directly contributed to the trauma that Zimbabwe is suffering from today\".{{sfn|Coltart|2007}} Godwin took a similar line, describing the emergency powers Smith used to combat black nationalists as \"draconian\";{{sfn|Godwin|2007}} he also pointed out that these \"levers of repression\" had formed the base for much of what Mugabe later did.{{sfn|Godwin|2007}} Lord Carrington spoke scathingly about Smith in a 2005 interview with [[Heidi Holland]], saying he disliked both Smith and Mugabe but would choose the latter if he \"absolutely had to choose\"; Smith was, in his opinion, \"a bigoted, stupid man\" responsible for all of Zimbabwe's problems.{{sfn|Holland|2009|p=64}}{{refn|Smith had a similarly low opinion of Carrington, condemning him in strong terms in ''The Great Betrayal'': \"During my time in the world of politics I have come into contact with my fair share of devious characters, but I regard Carrington as the most two-faced of them all.\"{{sfn|Smith|1997|p=365}}|group=n|name=\"carringtonsmith\"}}\n\nWhile acknowledging the privileged position whites had under Smith, several commentators have latterly agreed with his claims that many black Zimbabweans preferred him to Mugabe with hindsight, albeit a very low bar.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bevan|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Boynton|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Cowell|2007 b}}; {{Harvnb|Johnson|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Meredith|2007|p=17}}; {{Harvnb|The Times|2007}}; {{Harvnb|The Week|2007}}.</ref> \"Smith's image improved inversely as Mugabe's plummeted,\" Johnson wrote. \"When he walked the streets of Harare, Africans would almost queue up to grasp his hand and wish him well.\"{{sfn|Johnson|2007}} \"If you were to go to Harare today [in 2007] and ask ordinary black Zimbabweans who they would rather have as their leader\u2014Smith or Mugabe\u2014the answer would be almost unanimous\", Boynton asserted; \"And it would not be Mugabe.\"{{sfn|Boynton|2007}}\n\nSmith's death ignited condemnatory remarks in Zimbabwe's Mugabe-controlled state media. Deputy Minister of Information [[Bright Matonga]] accused Smith of having been a racist, blamed him for the deaths of thousands of people, and asserted that he would \"not be mourned or missed here by any decent person\".{{sfn|Chinaka|2007}} Reactions from Zimbabweans on the street were mixed, however; according to Western journalists, many expressed sadness.<ref>{{Harvnb|Bevan|2007}}; {{Harvnb|Raath|2007}}; {{Harvnb|The Week|2007}}.</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist|group=n|colwidth=40em}}\n\n'''References'''\n{{reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n'''Newspaper and journal articles'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite news\n|title=Zimbabweans praise 'generous' Ian Smith\n|first=Stephen\n|last=Bevan\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1570403/Zimbabweans-praise-generous-Ian-Smith.html\n|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]\n|location=London\n|date=20 November 2007\n|accessdate=7 January 2014\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news\n|title=Ian Smith defies Mugabe's threats and flies home\n|first=David\n|last=Blair\n|authorlink=David Blair (journalist)\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/zimbabwe/1373741/Ian-Smith-defies-Mugabes-threats-and-flies-home.html\n|work=The Daily Telegraph\n|location=London\n|date=8 November 2000\n|accessdate=19 November 2013\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news\n|title=Ian Smith is stripped of Zimbabwe citizenship\n|first=David\n|last=Blair\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/zimbabwe/1389134/Ian-Smith-is-stripped-of-Zimbabwe-citizenship.html\n|work=The Daily Telegraph\n|location=London\n|date=28 March 2002\n|accessdate=26 December 2013\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news\n|title=Ian Smith: Man whose folly unleashed Mugabe\n|last=Blair\n|first=David\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1569980/Ian-Smith-Man-whose-folly-unleashed-Mugabe.html\n|work=The Daily Telegraph\n|location=London\n|date=20 November 2007\n|accessdate=22 November 2013\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news\n|title=Former Rhodesian PM Ian Smith dies\n|last1=Blair\n|first1=David\n|last2=Thornycroft\n|first2=Peta\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/1569979/Former-Rhodesian-PM-Ian-Smith-dies.html\n|work=The Daily Telegraph\n|location=London\n|date=20 November 2007\n|accessdate=7 January 2014\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news\n|title=Ian Smith has sadly been proved right\n|last=Boynton\n|first=Graham\n|authorlink=Graham Boynton\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/3644217/Ian-Smith-has-sadly-been-proved-right.html\n|work=The Daily Telegraph\n|location=London\n|date=22 November 2007\n|accessda