and Porsche form Joint Venture|accessdate=2017-11-03}}</ref>\n* Capable of charging certain cars (e.g. [[Porsche Taycan]] in 2021<ref>{{cite web |title=Porsche Taycan to have 250 kW charging at launch, promised 350 kW coming in 2021 |url=https://electrek.co/2019/07/17/porsche-taycan-250-kw-charging-launch-promised-350-kw/ |publisher=Electrek}}</ref>)<ref name=\"porsche2\">{{cite web|url=https://newsroom.porsche.com/en/company/porsche-ionity-europe-high-power-charging-network-joint-venture-electromobility-14439.html|website=newsroom.porsche.com|title=Launch of Pan-European High-Power Charging Network IONITY|accessdate=2017-11-03}}</ref> up to 80 per cent in just 15 minutes\n*Charging stations have from 2 to 8 CCS plugs on each, with 4 plugs per station in average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ionity.ev-info.eu/statistics|title=Status Tracker for IONITY HPC|website=ionity.ev-info.eu|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n*Charging stations have slightly different design, depending on country and manufacturer. \n*Most of stations (in 2019) were produced by Tritium and ABB, and some by Porsche itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ionity.ev-info.eu/statistics|title=Status Tracker for IONITY HPC|website=ionity.ev-info.eu|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\nCurrent members include BMW Group, Daimler, Ford, Volkswagen, Audi, and Porsche. It was announced on September 9 2019 that Hyundai Motor group would bring Hyundai and Kia brands on board as strategic partners.<ref name=\"hyundai\">{{cite web|url=https://ionity.eu/en/news-storage/hyundai-on-board.html|title=IONITY WELCOMES NEW SHAREHOLDER HYUNDAI MOTOR GROUP ON BOARD |date=2019-09-09 |accessdate=2019-09-09}}</ref>\n\n== Rollout ==\nIONITY rollout table: number of open stations per country per quarter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ionity.evapi.de/#/|title=IonityTracker|last=|first=|date=|website=ionity.evapi.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  \n!2019_Q4!! 2019_Q3 !! 2019_Q2 !! 2019_Q1 !! 2018_Q4 !! 2018_Q3 !! 2018_Q2\n|-\n! Germany\n|69\n| 53 || 39 || 26 || 21 || 2 || 2\n|-\n! France\n|43\n| 26 || 17 || 10 || 5 || 2 || 0\n|-\n! Austria\n|16\n| 13 || 11 || 9 || 7 || 2 || 0\n|-\n! Norway\n|13\n| 12 || 12 || 6 || 4 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! Sweden\n|14\n| 10 || 7 || 3 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! Switzerland\n|9\n| 8 || 8 || 8 || 6 || 3 || 1\n|-\n! Belgium\n|7\n| 7 || 5 || 3 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! Denmark\n|6\n| 5 || 5 || 5 || 1 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! Netherlands\n|7\n| 5 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! United Kingdom\n|3\n| 3 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! Ireland\n|4\n| 3 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! Italy\n|2\n| 2 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! Hungary\n|3\n| 2 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! Slovenia\n|1\n| 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n!Finland\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n!Spain\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n!Czech Republic\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n!Total\n|202\n|150\n|112\n|71\n|45\n|10\n|3\n|}\n=== 2017 ===\nThe company claimed that a total of 20 stations would open to the public, located on major roads in multiple European countries through partnerships with Tank & Rast, [[Circle K]] and [[OMV]].<ref name=\"ionity\"/> By the end of 2017, no stations were open to the public.\n\n=== 2018 ===\nFirst IONITY charging station was opened on 24 April 2018 at [[Brohltal]]-Ost on the [[Bundesautobahn 61|A61 motorway]] in Germany's [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.electrans.co.uk/ionity-opens-first-charging-station/|title=Ionity opens first charging station - ElecTrans|website=www.electrans.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\nBy August 2018, 7 stations were open: 1 in Germany, 1 in Austria, 2 in France, 2 in Switzerland, and 1 in Denmark, with 4-6 chargers on each. 4 more stations are marked as coming soon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ionity.eu/locations/|title=Charging - ionity.eu|website=www.ionity.eu|language=de|access-date=2018-08-11}}</ref>\n\nBy October 2018, 10 stations with 4-6 CCS charger plugs were open, 20 stations are marked as \"now building\". Charging cost for the rest of 2018 was established as 8 (\u20ac8, or \u00a38, or 8CHF depending on country) per charging session (no power or time restrictions). In Scandinavia the session fee will be 80 NOK / SEK / DKK. The European Union countries currently remaining without published plans for IONITY chargers include: Bulgaria, Croatia, Republic of Cyprus, Czechia, Estonia, Finland, Greece, Hungary, Ireland, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Malta, Poland, Portugal, Romania, Slovakia, Slovenia, Spain, and the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ionity.eu/en/where-and-how.html|title=IONITY - WHERE AND HOW|website=ionity.eu|access-date=October 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2018, 47 stations on map are marked open  and 45 as now building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ionity.eu/|title=ionity.eu|access-date=2019-01-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 ===\nThe 100th charging station was open to public in [[Rygge]], Norway on 27 May 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ionity.eu/en/news-storage/ionity-achieves-significant-milestone-100th-high-power-charging-hpc-charging-park-goes-into-operation-in-rygge-norway.html|title=IONITY achieves significant milestone: 100th High-Power-Charging (HPC-) Park goes into operation in Rygge, Norway - News storage - IONITY EU|website=ionity.eu|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref> On 20 December 2019 200th charging station was completed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ionity.evapi.de/#/charts|title=Development of Ionity network size |website=ionity.evapi.de|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 ===\nIn 2017, IONITY planned to have \"implemented and operate about 400 fast charging stations across European major thoroughfares until 2020\".<ref name=\"ionity\" />\n\nIn January 2020, IONITY announced that customers with no contract would be charged 0.79 euros per kWh.<ref>[https://insideevs.com/news/393393/ionity-announced-a-kwh-based-pricing-scheme/ IONITY Announces A kWh-Based Charger Pricing Plan] - Inside EVS, 17 January 2020</ref> The network was criticized for the 500% rate increase for those drivers without a subscription plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2020/01/17/ionity-increases-electric-vehicle-charging-prices-500-percent-january-31/|title=IONITY to increase electric vehicle charging prices 500%|last=Benoit|first=Charles|date=2020-01-17|website=Electrek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> German automakers shared discounted rates for Connected Mobility Service Providers network participants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fleeteurope.com/en/new-energies/europe/analysis/ionity-network-dramatically-increases-ev-fast-charging-costs|title=IONITY network dramatically increases EV fast charging costs|last=Jonathan|date=2020-01-21|website=Fleet Europe|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> For example, Mercedes-Benz announced a reduced IONITY charging price of 0.29 euros per charged kilowatt hour for Mercedes' me Charge users.<ref>[https://insideevs.com/news/394015/mercedes-me-charge-300000-charging-points/ Mercedes me Charge Offers Access To 300,000 Charging Points], Inside EVs, 21 January 2020</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Charging stations]]\n", "name_user": "Historiese Kluise", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharging stations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IONITY"}
